<HEAD>Immigrant Convicted Of Killing Five Faces Execution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with condemned man huddled with
LSU basketball coach, spurning last meals; picking up 6th graf pvs
``Lowenfield, a...'' ADDS byline. Ruling from federal appeals court
is still pending and execution could be as late as 4 a.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENT PRINCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Guyanese immigrant convicted of killing his girlfriend and four members of her family in a jealous rage lost appeals Tuesday in state and federal courts in his last-minute bid to avoid the electric chair. The <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and then <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beer </PERSON> refused to put off the execution of <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON>, 34, which is set for early Wednesday. <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON>'s attorneys then went to the 5th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> with the plea that he is mentally ill and therefore unable to understand the death penalty. At the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penitentiary </ORGANIZATION>, Warden <PERSON> Hilton </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> was still hoping for a fifth delay of as many execution dates. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> spurned the condemned's customary last meal and spent the evening with <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, the head basketball coach from <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, widely recognized as a motivational speaker, had been corresponding with <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> since he took the <ORGANIZATION> LSU </ORGANIZATION> team on a tour of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s death row in 1984, <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said. A Catholic priest and nun also were with <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON>, the warden said. <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON>, a welder from <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION> who came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1981 on a work permit, was convicted in 1984 in the August 1982 slayings of his estranged girlfriend, who was a <ORGANIZATION> Jefferson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parish </ORGANIZATION> sheriff's deputy, and four others. The case has already been appealed unsuccessfully to both the state's highest court and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Lawyers based their latest appeal on a recent psychological study that found the prisoner to be a paranoid schizophrenic. `` There is a serious question about <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON>'s competency to be executed due to his mental illness,'' said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Menadue </PERSON>, attorney for the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Capital Defense Project. She said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled that people who can not understand what it means to be executed may not be put to death. Before the trial, <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> was found competent, and he refused to allow his lawyers to use insanity as a defense, insisting instead that he was in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> at the time the family was killed. But no witnesses backed up his story of being out of state. The denial of the stay was issued without further comment from the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> majority, but the one member who backed the appeal issued a brief dissent. `` The clinical psychologist who spent five hours with the defendant concluded: ` Lowenfield indicated that he is currently unable to understand the death penalty,''' Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> wrote. He noted that criminal law calls for halting prosecution when there are reasonable grounds to doubt a defendant's sanity, and for going ahead after that only when the defendant is found to have the mental capacity to do so. Prosecutors said <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> barged into his girlfriend's house in <LOCATION> Marrero </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> suburb, and shot everybody there. The victims were the girlfriend, <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, 27; her daughter, <PERSON> Shantel </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON>, 4; her stepfather, <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, 45; her mother, <PERSON> Myrtle </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, 44; and the little girl's father, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON>, 33. The prosecution said <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> was jealous of Miss <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. They said the couple had lived together in a stormy relationship until earlier in the summer of 1982 when he set the house on fire and she moved out. Investigators found a notebook full of obscenities and threats. In one place he wrote, `` She have to go to the wormes she took all I work for then leave to go and be with <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> but I just can not take it eany more.'' <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> was arrested two months later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Parts of the evidence against him were letters he wrote Miss <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>' relatives while he was jailed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. One said <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON> had grabbed the child as a shield and <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> had shot both of them. On trial, <PERSON> Lowenfield </PERSON> insisted on an alibi defense, saying he was in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, looking for work at the time of the murders. After a separate trial to determine the penalty, jurors came back three times saying they could not decide whether he should die. Prodded on by the judge, they decided on the fourth try to condemn him to death.
