 The hijacking drama of a Kuwaiti airliner seized April 5 entered its second week today. Here is a list of prolonged hijack incidents: JULY 23-SEPT. 1, 1968 _ <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, is diverted to <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nationalists Forty days later, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> releases the last 12 passengers held hostage. SEPT. 6-30, 1970 _ Palestinian commandos hijack three airliners to a desert airstrip outside <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. Most passengers are released by Sept. 12, when the Palestinians blow up the three planes, but 54 people are held hostage for 24 days. JUNE 15-JULY 1, 1985 _ Shiite Moslem gunmen hijack <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> Athens-to-Rome flight to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Some passengers are released but 40 men are held hostage. One hostage, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stetham </PERSON>, is shot dead; 17 days later the remaining 39 are released. MARCH 2-15, 1981 _ Pakistani hijackers commandeer Pakistani jet, diverting it to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and on to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. All 148 hostages are released after 13 days aboard the plane.
