<HEAD>Convicted Rapist-Mutilator Says He's Pursuing Legal Action Against
Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man convicted of raping and maiming a teenager almost 10 years ago is seeking a criminal investigation into his allegation that the woman actually kidnapped him, a newspaper reported Monday. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>, who is scheduled to be freed April 25 after serving seven years and nine months in prison and a year on parole, said he filed a complaint in <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Placer </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Marin </LOCATION> counties requesting the woman's arrest, the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ledger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Antioch </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>, 60, was convicted in 1979 of raping <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>, then 15, and hacking off her forearms with an ax on Sept. 29, 1978. He was sentenced to 14 years and 4 months in prison, which was reduced for good behavior and work credit. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> said he will move to <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> to spend his `` first few days'' of freedom with a church group after his release, the newspaper said, but he did not rule out a return to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> has spent the last 10 months of his parole in a trailer on the grounds of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quentin </LOCATION> state prison for his own protection after residents of several northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> communities protested against his planned parole last year. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>, who expressed anxiety about his parole at that time, has moved to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and recently told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> through an intermediary that she did not want to be interviewed further about <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON>. The Ledger said it obtained a copy of a 12-page, typewritten complaint in which <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> alleges <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> committed kidnap for the purpose of robbery and use of two deadly weapons. According to the Ledger, the complaint said <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> was heading to <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, when he picked up <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> hitchhiking in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and agreed to take her to <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>. The complaint said <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> began smoking PCP, a hallucinogen, then said she wanted to go to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, became abusive and poked <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> with a three-foot surveyor stick, the newspaper reported. `` -LRB- She -RRB- told me that if I did not comply with her wishes she would poke out my eyes, smash my face, and hurt, hurt, hurt me and say that I raped her,'' the newspaper quoted the complaint as saying. The complaint also alleges <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> threatened <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> with a six-inch fish-scaling knife, the newspaper reported. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> claims he drove <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Galt </LOCATION>, 20 miles south of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, where he picked up two male hitchhikers who joined <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> in extorting money from <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> to buy drugs, the newspaper reported. The complaint says <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> drove north and left <LOCATION> Vincent </LOCATION> in a `` low-rent district'' in <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> and never saw her again, the newspaper reported. Although not in the complaint, <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> has repeatedly claimed he allowed one of the hitchhikers to drive while he was drinking, passed out, then awoke to find <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> was gone but her clothes were still in the van. The hitchhikers, he has contended, committed the crimes. Authorities, however, have maintained the two hitchhikers never existed. <PERSON> Singleton </PERSON> said in a telephone interview he mailed the complaint Saturday to authorities in the two counties, but court clerks in both counties said Monday morning they had not received the complaints, the Ledger reported.
