<HEAD>Brazilian Drought, European Demand Raise Soybean Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean market prices are averaging the most in three years because of greater world demand and a tightening of available supplies, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysis shows. Drought has damaged <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s soybean crop, and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> has increased its demand for the oilseed, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. That has helped whittle down <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean stockpiles and boost prices. The supply-and-demand report said soybean prices now could average in the range of $ 5.50 to $ 5.80 per bushel in the marketing year that began last Sept. 1, up from $ 5.35 to $ 5.75 forecast in March. Prices averaged $ 4.78 per bushel in the 1986-87 season. According to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> records, that would be the most since soybeans averaged $ 5.84 per bushel in 1984-85. They were $ 7.83 in the 1983-84 marketing year. Soybean exports were forecast at 785 million bushels, up from 760 million indicated last month and the 757 million bushels shipped in 1986-87. Wheat exports also have improved, due mainly to subsidized sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under the department's Export Enhancement Program, or EEP. In all, exports in the wheat marketing year that runs through May 31 are estimated at 1.6 billion bushels, a 60 percent increase from 1 billion bushels shipped in 1986-87. Average market prices for this season were put at $ 2.55 per bushel, up from $ 2.42 last year. Corn exports also are up, rising to an estimated 1.7 billion bushels in the corn marketing year that began last Sept. 1, compared with 1.5 billion bushels in 1986-87. Market prices of corn were forecast to average $ 1.65 to $ 1.85 per bushel this season, up from $ 1.50 in 1986-87.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Department scientists are looking at the neem tree of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as a possible source of material to prevent the formation of aflatoxin, a food toxin that occurs in nature. Aflatoxin can be produced by fungi that forms on some farm crops under certain conditions, including corn and oilseeds. Laboratory tests with animals have shown that aflatoxin is among the most powerful cancer-causing agents known, and <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> has called it a `` potential'' hazard to humans. <PERSON> Deepak </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhatnagar </PERSON> said in a report released here that as a child in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> his parents used to put leaves of the neem tree inside containers of wheat to keep insects from the grain. Now, as a <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> scientist, he has found that the leaves may also block fungi from producing aflatoxin. In tests at the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> center in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bhatnagar </PERSON> made solutions containing neem leaves. He found that the solutions did n't kill the fungi but did block more than 98 percent of the aflatoxin they normally would have produced. The fungi that produce the toxin are Aspergillus flavus and A. parasiticus. <PERSON> Bhatnagar </PERSON> said the results were `` promising, but preliminary'' and that greenhouse studies with cotton are now being planned. The ornamental neem is also known as margosa and nim. More than 80 insect pests, including Mexican bean beetles, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> potato beetles, tobacco budworms and carpet beetles are repelled by neem extracts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spice imports totaled about $ 439 million last year, up 12 percent from 1986, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The rise was due mainly to larger imports of vanilla beans, white pepper, nutmeg and mace, cassia, cumin, anise, capsicum peppers, laurel and thyme, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. Higher prices of many of the items also were a factor. `` Saffron prices have soared in recent months, reflecting a short Spanish crop,'' the report said. Also, it added, cesium contamination from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s nuclear mishap at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> two years ago `` has kept supplies tight and prices firm for several Mediterranean-area herbs such as oregano, laurel, rosemary and sage.
</TEXT>
