<FIRST>r w PM-FinanceMinisters     04-12 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Finance Ministers,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Plan Receiving Warm Reception</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> seems to be making progress in his drive to get the world's top economic powers to use the price of gold and other commodities to help them coordinate economic policies. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> took economic leaders by surprise when he advanced the idea last September, with some countries openly skeptical. But <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has demonstrated considerable skill as one of the administration's top negotiators and officials indicated Monday that the world's seven top industrial countries are likely to give formal approval to <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s commodity-index proposal on Wednesday. The seven nations, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, will hold high-level talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as part of the spring meeting of the 151-nation <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. A senior <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, briefing reporters Monday, said the administration is `` hopeful there will be some agreement'' by the seven countries to adopt the commodity-basket proposal. The official spoke on condition his name not be used. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has stressed that he is not proposing a return to the gold standard, the system in use for 25 years after World War II. For most of that time, the price of gold was fixed at $ 35 an ounce and the currencies of other countries were pegged at fixed exchange rates to the dollar. That system broke down in the early 1970s under the weight of higher inflation and a rising flow of international capital between countries. It was replaced with today's floating exchange rate system under which the value of each nation's currency is set on the open market. But the extreme volatility in floating rates, especially for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, has driven the big industrial countries in search of ways to stabilize exchange rates. One method that <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has pushed since the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> economic summit in 1986 has been the use of a variety of economic indicators to monitor each country's performance in helping to sustain worldwide growth. This group of indicators includes individual growth rates, inflation and trade balances. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s proposal would add gold and other commodity prices to the list of economic yardsticks the countries use to coordinate policies. This approach would introduce a price-sensitive measure into the economic planning process. In addition to gold, other commodities which might be included are iron ore, copper, rubber, cotton, wheat, rice, corn, coffee and tea. If the price of these commodities rose in particular countries, those nations would be encouraged to boost interest rates to fight inflation. But if commodity prices were falling, the countries would know they had room to cut interest rates and stimulate economic growth without danger of inflation. Some countries, in particular <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, have opposed the commodity index because they see it as a device that would be used to goad them into achieving faster growth at the risk of sparking inflation. But in a television interview Monday, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the seven top industrial countries were in basic agreement at present over the steps needed to stabilize exchange rates. `` The major industrialized countries of the world obviously favor stability of exchange rates and we have been very pleased with the stability we have seen since our last meeting in December,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' program. Last Dec. 22, the seven countries pledged to support the dollar, which at the time was under heavy selling pressure. That commitment was backed up by massive intervention, the process by which governments buy weak currencies such as the dollar to drive up the price.
</TEXT>
