<HEAD>Congress More Resistant than Public to Social Security Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans are more willing than their representatives in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to consider changes in the Social Security system, but no single option for cutting costs has broad public support, according to a survey. The public also strongly favors pulling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops out of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as a way to reduce the federal budget deficit, according to the survey by the League of Concerned Americans, a <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, N.C.-based non-profit group. The league commissioned the nationwide poll as part of a project called `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Budget,'' an effort to determine national spending priorities from a non-Washington perspective. It planned to release a suggested budget today. `` A lot of things that are perceptually true in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> ... are not that way across the country,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Rasmussen </PERSON>, founder of the league. For example, an informal congressional survey showed 80 percent of the members favored leaving the Social Security system untouched. Only 34 percent favored that option in the nationwide poll. However, people differed over what changes should be made, the poll showed. From a list of options, 21 percent favored making the system voluntary and 25 percent supported raising the retirement age to allow a drop in the Social Security tax. Only 6 percent favored cutting cost-of-living adjustments for retirees _ the most frequently mentioned option when <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> considers cutbacks. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been holding hearings this year on what lawmakers call `` burden sharing'' _ forcing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies to take on more of the cost of defending against the Soviet bloc. The informal survey of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> showed only 12 percent said they would favor gradually withdrawing `` a substantial portion'' of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops from <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> over the next 20 years. However, more than three out of four citizens polled supported the idea. The poll was conducted for the league by <ORGANIZATION> Marketwise </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The random sample of 519 respondents has a margin of error of 4.3 percentage points. Despite the 1983 changes in the Social Security, which included raising taxes to build up big surpluses over the next few years, more than a fourth of the people polled still doubt whether their benefits will be there when they retire, according to the survey. `` I think there is a real temptation -LRB- to spend the money -RRB- if there are surpluses,'' said <PERSON> Rasmussen </PERSON>. Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday he would propose a resolution to put <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on record opposing the current accounting system which allows Social Security surpluses to hide the true size of the government's operating deficit <PERSON> Rasmussen </PERSON>, a business entrepreneur who with his father founded the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> sports network in 1978, said he hoped the league would help prod the politicians to keep working toward a balanced budget. The results were being presented to the new national commission on the deficit, which will make recommendations for the next president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on ways to cut red ink, he said.
