<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and other big grain producers should create a fund that would help develop farming in the Third World, French Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON> says such a plan would help narrow the growing gap between rich and poor countries. <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON> spoke Monday at an open meeting with <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials and farm experts. `` Public opinion can not understand that politicans in the developed countries are unable to put the grains stored in American and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> silos into the stomachs of men and women in developing countries,'' he said. Meanwhile, both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are each spending about $ 30 billion a year to subsidize farmers, he said. During a news conference he described his proposal, under which grain producers would fix a floor price for grain at a level that would not stimulate new production. They would then contribute part of the difference between the floor price and actual selling prices to a fund that <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON> likened to the Marshall Plan, which helped western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> recover from World War II. The fund would be used to improve farming in Third World countries. He estimated that it could furnish $ 1.8 billion to $ 4 billion a year from exporters of grain amd could be increased by voluntary countributions from rich importers, such as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Amstutz </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator for world farm issues, came out strongly against any plan to set prices and limit production. He said one reason it would not work is that all producers could not be included and those who did not join would increase their production. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been pushing a plan to phase out by the end of the century all subsidies affecting world trade in farm products.
