<HEAD>Sandinistas Propose Renewed Technical Talks With Contras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs bgng: Marta Sacasa... with 3 grafs rebels
responding to government proposal for techical meeting to resume
Wednesday. Pick up 5th graf pvs: A preliminary peace...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Monday proposed a resumption of talks with rebels on details of a cease-fire plan after negotiations ended last week in disagreement over arms shipments. The Sandinista government suggested the technical discussions be resumed Wednesday or Thursday in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the capital. It also proposed that the rebels, known as Contras, send an advance team to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Tuesday to prepare for discussions Sandinista and rebel political leaders are scheduled to hold on Friday. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> who is a member of the special negotiating commission released a statement late Monday saying the technical talks should resume at noon on Wednesday in the border village of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. The statement said the <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION>'s ranking political leaders would travel to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Friday for negotiations, based on progress at the <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> talks. There was no immediate response from the government. <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON>' statement said the Contras would send an advance delegation to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> Thursday to prepare for the political talks. It said the Contra representatives would include <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON>, secretary of the directorate of the Contras' umbrella Nicaraguan Resistance group, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadhagen </PERSON>. A preliminary peace plan signed March 23 in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> called for the two sides to hold technical discussions to work out details of a 60-day cease-fire that went into effect April 1. The talks between military commanders are to spell out how the Contras are to gather in cease-fire zones. During the truce, the two sides are to hold negotiations leading to a permanent agreement to end more than six years of war between the U.S.-backed Contras and the government. Military leaders have held six days of technical talks since March 28 at <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, 90 miles south of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and beside the Costa Rican border. They have agreed only on seven zones in which the Contras are to gather but have failed to decide on security measures and how the rebels are to receive supplies in the zones. The meetings ended Friday after the Contras asked for a recess of several days to discuss a 25-point plan the government proposed. The Contras earlier offered a 34-point plan. Last week the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> suggested the technical talks be resumed Friday, when the political leaders are to hold their discussions. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichler </PERSON>, an American lawyer negotiating for the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>, said over the weekend that there were only two points of contention in the proposal presented by the Contras. The Contra proposals would allow the rebels to receive arms, ammunition and war materiel while in the zones. It also would ban the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> from receiving any military aid, which is supplied by the Soviet bloc. <PERSON> Reichler </PERSON> described those two points as `` absolutely unacceptable.'' The original cease-fire plan would permit the Contras to receive only food and basic supplies channeled through a neutral organization, such as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. Political leaders of both sides had been scheduled to meet last Wednesday in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. The rebels postponed them, saying the technical talks had not advanced enough to move toward political issues. The rebels also have said they will not participate in this week's high-level political talks unless they are free to meet with opposition leaders. The government maintains that the peace agreement specifies Contra representation in politics begins only after the rebels move into the cease-fire zones.
