<HEAD>Soviet Team Arrives To Discuss Logistics Of INF Inspections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain; arrival expected in mid-to-late
afternoon.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A team of Soviet officials is readying for a second round of talks aimed at sorting through arrangements for verifying the arms treaty eliminating intermediate-range nuclear weapons. The Soviet team of 10 to 14 military and civilian officials was due in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> today and planned to meet behind closed doors with an American group starting on Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. According to one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official who asked not to be named, the talks will extend at least to Saturday and will focus on a variety of `` housekeeping details'' that must be settled before the two sides begin compliance inspections. `` Some of the topics on the plate include living quarters for inspectors, call signs for aircraft traveling in each country, the logistics of moving and putting in place the equipment we'll need and what equipment we're planning to use, and even how we deal with the news media,'' said the source. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> want to reach agreement on such details in advance of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote on ratifying the new treaty to ensure a smooth start for the compliance inspections, the official added. Signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on Dec. 8, the new treaty specifies that all nuclear missiles in the two superpower arsenals with a range of roughly 300 miles to 3,500 miles be destroyed within three years. Within the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, the Pentagon has created an organization known as the <ORGANIZATION> On-Site </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> to verify <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> compliance with the new treaty. The head of that agency, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brig </ORGANIZATION>. Gen. <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON>, will lead the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team in this week's discussions. The two sides held their first round of talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last month. The <ORGANIZATION> OSIA </ORGANIZATION> will be responsible for escorting Soviet inspectors who travel to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to monitor the removal and destruction of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nuclear weapons, as well as performing the same role inside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> by visiting Russian facilities and deployment sites.
