e <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>, which has made the trade bill its top legislative priority for six years, has threatened to withdraw its support for it entirely if the layoff notices are eliminated. `` I could understand our so-called trading partners being opposed to the bill,'' <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-Treasurer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> said Monday. `` But he's -LRB- <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> -RRB- supposed to be the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Under the provision, companies with more than 100 employees would be required to give 60 days advance notice when they intend to close a plant or lay off one-third or more of its workforce. However, the layoffs would have to total at least 50 workers to trigger the mandatory notices. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> `` superconferees'' are scheduled to start meeting today in hopes of getting a final version of the trade bill by Thursday or Friday for separate votes in each house on final passage. Without citing specific provisions, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said in his weekend radio address Saturday he still has `` very _ underline very _ serious reservations'' about the bill. `` The bottom line is this: I will veto a bad trade bill before I let a bad trade bill veto our economy.'' While administration officials have outlined objections to several provisions, congressional leaders describe most of the protests as `` padding'' for its vehement opposition to the mandatory layoff notices. `` It's a classic game of everybody trying to figure out what the other guy's bottom line is,'' said one legislative aide, who acknowledged one purpose of the candidates' letters is to counter administration veto threats. Just a week ago, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> wrote <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> she would be `` forced to recommend that the president veto the bill ... if these protectionist mandatory plant closing and layoff requirements remain.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> task force last year called advance notices `` an essential component of a readjustment program'' for helping laid off workers get new jobs, but stopped short of saying the notices should be mandated. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>, two of every three workers laid off in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> receive no advance notice. The average notice, according to a separate survey by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, is 14 days for white-collar workers and seven days for blue-collar workers.
