 <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>'s rhinoceros may be an unlikely cross between a bull and a <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION>, but he says he'll miss the life-size, metallic sculpture when it moves to a <LOCATION> Ripley </LOCATION>'s Believe It Or Not museum `` The mountains are no place for an 8-year-old rhinoceros,'' <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said. `` It's time he moved to a lower elevation and a warmer climate.'' The rhino was made about eight years ago from old steel automobile bumpers by `` bumper sculpture'' artist <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bedford </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Salida </LOCATION> resident. <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> bought it for display in front of his hardware business on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 50. When the business closed a year ago, the rhino moved to the front lawn of <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>'s home. `` We felt it did n't belong in a private yard,'' <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said. `` It should be in a public place, where people can see and appreciate it.'' So <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> put the rhino up for sale, advertising it at a gallery in <LOCATION> Taos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Bedford </ORGANIZATION> now works. Last week, word came that the rhino was sold to <PERSON> Ripley </PERSON>'s Believe It Or Not Museum in <LOCATION> Laguna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. Still, <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> says, he'll miss the old beast. `` The rhino brought a lot of interesting comments and situations when we were at the store,'' he said. `` There was the old rancher from <LOCATION> Saguache </LOCATION>, for example. He showed up one morning, just as I was opening the store, and he stood outside for a long time, studying that rhinoceros. `` ` When he finally came in he said, ` I know where that came from. ... It's a cross between a Brahma bull and a Buick.'''
