<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     04-12 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Moving Toward Approval of $1.1 Trillion Federal Budget</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Senate resumes debate 11:30 a.m. EDT; top planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is moving toward approval of a $ 1.1 trillion federal budget for fiscal 1989 that some lawmakers say does more to mask the size of the government's enormous deficit than it does to slash it. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders predicted that despite those reservations the chamber could approve the spending plan as early as today. The proposal, which has received rare bipartisan support, cleared its first procedural hurdle Monday when senators voted 83-0 to begin debating the budget resolution. The fiscal 1989 blueprint estimates a deficit of $ 136 billion, precisely the target set by the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law for the next fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1. This year's deficit is expected to reach $ 146.7 billion. But helping to keep the red ink down is a $ 46 billion surplus the Social Security system is expected to amass next year. Even though that money is being built up in anticipation of retirements by the baby boomers in the early 21st century _ and can not be used for anything else _ the annual surpluses were included in the budget's arithmetic and make the deficit look smaller. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, like the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, relied on an optimistic administration economic forecast to arrive at its projected deficit. Had the lawmakers used the less cheerful projections of their own <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the red ink would have been $ 35 billion higher. `` We need to quit fooling ourselves in talking about a $ 136 billion deficit,'' Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, chairman of the budget committee, said during debate. `` It's just not correct.'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., planned to introduce an amendment that would urge <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to stop using Social Security surpluses in calculating the deficit Other amendments were anticipated to shift money among several domestic programs. But the main fights that normally dominate budget debates _ how to balance domestic and military spending, and whether to raise taxes _ are not present this year. Those questions were settled last fall, when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and congressional leaders reached their so-called budget summit agreement. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget resolution obeys the summit agreement's limits in calling for $ 294 billion in military spending next year, $ 16.1 billion for foreign assistance and $ 169.2 billion for domestic programs in which spending is not set by automatic formulas. In addition, there will be no new taxes beyond the $ 14 billion called for in the summit and already enacted into law. `` I do n't think we can afford this year to breach the summit agreement,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the budget panel. `` I think we ought to enforce it, and I think we've done that rather well.'' With the major fights out of the way, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed its version of the budget resolution March 23 on a bipartisan 319-102 vote. In that chamber, as in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, lawmakers have some significant differences with the domestic priorities <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> set in the budget he submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in February. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal does not eliminate or severely slash a series of federal mass transit and economic development programs, as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> wanted. It also calls for about $ 1 billion more than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. But, in line with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recommendations, it would increase spending for AIDS research, education, space, science and drug enforcement. The budget resolution does not require the president's signature, but the two chambers must agree on an identical version before it takes effect The document will be used later as a blueprint by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> when it passes bills that actually provide the money for federal agencies.
