<HEAD>``Babette's Feast'' Named Best Foreign Film</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oscars, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` <PERSON> Babette </PERSON>'s Feast,'' a Danish movie about two pious, unmarried sisters who take a political refugee into their home, won best foreign language film at the Academy Awards. `` It's the first time a Danish movie can take an Oscar home,'' director <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Axel </PERSON>, who spent 14 years trying to get the movie made, said as he accepted the award Monday night. `` I am very grateful for this honor and I want to thank you Academy members from the bottom of my heart.'' Also nominated were `` Au <ORGANIZATION> Revoir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Les </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enfants </ORGANIZATION>,'' <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>; `` Course Completed,'' <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>; `` The Family,'' <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, and `` Pathfinder,'' <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> has divided his career between his native <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Babette </PERSON>'s Feast'' portrayed the lives of the sisters who took in a political refugee named <PERSON> Babette </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Stephane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audran </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- fleeing the French revolution. The refugee, a former world-class chef, later repays their kindness by devoting her winnings from a lottery to creation of a sumptuous feast. The film, titled `` Babettes Gaestebud'' in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, was based on a short story by <PERSON> Isak </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinesen </PERSON>, whose book `` Out of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'' was the basis for the 1986 best movie Oscar winner. Following his success with `` <PERSON> Babette </PERSON>'s Feast,'' <PERSON> Axel </PERSON> has said he hopes to film a project he has nurtured for 20 years _ a version of `` Hamlet'' based on the earliest histories of the saga from which <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> borrowed his plot. Thirty countries submitted movies for consideration as best foreign film for this year's Academy Awards ceremony. The record for foreign submissions was 32 in 1984, according to <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Werden </PERSON>, an Academy spokesman.
