<HEAD>Merger Of Rivals Brings Virtual One-Party State To Zimbabwe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The merger of two black political groups that led the war to end white-minority rule in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, then <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION>, virtually abolishes one of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s few multiparty states. `` We have one <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, one nation and one national army. We will be stronger if we have one party,'' President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> said at a weekend rally. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, an avowed Marxist, led his party to victory in elections held after a British-sponsored peace conference ended years of guerrilla warfare and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> became independent in April 1980. His chief rival in the balloting was <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>, one of the country's wealthiest men. They had organized guerrilla armies in the 1960s to gain black-majority rule and toward the end of the campaign joined forces. But the alliance collapsed in 1980, after <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s resounding victory and scattered clashes followed between the supporters of both sides. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, advocated one-party rule and was opposed by <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peoples </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. But last week, a Peoples Union convention endorsed a merger approved in December by <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON>. On Saturday, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> conference delegates approved the agreement. It is expected that by the end of the year, <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s party will be by law the sole political party in this southern African nation. Opponents say <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s party will turn capitalist <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> into a socialist state with <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> becoming a rubber-stamp legislature. Supporters claim the merger will bring unity to an area divided by tribal differences and with political structures too fragile to withstand the rigors of Western-style multiparty politics. The merger does not basically expand <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s solid power base. He has been in control since his party won 57 of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s 100 seats in pre-independence elections and has increased the number the number since then to 85. But the merger will give him the support to revise the British-drafted constitution that dictated a multiparty system for the first 10 years after independence. The constitution can be changed during that period only by a unanimous parliemtary vote. The new <ORGANIZATION> united </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> will control all but one legislative seat. A businessman, <PERSON> Goodson </PERSON> <PERSON> Sithole </PERSON>, is the only representative of a small party that broke from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. He could block the one-party move with a negative vote, but is n't expected to stand up against the combined weight of the two main parties. For <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, 64, his goal of creating a Marxist-Leninist state has involved more rhetoric then reality in his eight years in power. <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> remains one of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s staunchest capitalist countries and whites, internally and externally, still control the economy. But <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> has made it clear he expects the country's leaders to be socialists. `` Surely, they -LRB- his opponents -RRB- can not be allowed to walk our public path of socialism with us, when at the same time they have charted for themselves their own private path of capitalism,'' he said at the convention on Saturday. For 70-year-old <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> the merger is a chance for the `` old lion,'' as his supporters call him, to leave the political scene with some of his former glory. <PERSON> Nkomo </PERSON> had been dumped from a coalition government shortly after the 1980 elections. But when the merger plans were announced in December after three years of negotiations, he became one of three senior ministers in the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. In the new <ORGANIZATION> united </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> he will be second vice-president _ the No. 3 slot.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> has covered southern African politics for three years.
