<HEAD>Witnesses Say It Has Become Easier To Get Testimony From Mafiosi</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RETRANSMITTING to add writethru designator and correct
overline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Omerta _ the <ORGANIZATION> Mafia </ORGANIZATION> code of silence _ is crumbling as authorities find it easier to turn mobsters into witnesses, according to top law enforcement officials and a former member of the Sicilian Mafia. `` When the going gets tough, the smart change sides,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON>, acting chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Criminal Division, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on Monday. `` The number and stature of convicted mobsters ` flipping' to the government's side in recent years is unprecedented.'' Before <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON> testified at the most extensive <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> organized crime hearings in a quarter-century, former Sicilian mobster <PERSON> Tommaso </PERSON> <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> helped prove <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON>'s point. Shielded by a screen to protect the public from seeing him, <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> said the Mafia in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> has changed so drastically because of the drug trade that `` I no longer feel bound by the code of ` omerta.''' He testified before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Permanent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> on Investigations, which held dramatic hearings on organized crime a quarter-century ago. The chief witness then was <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Valachi </PERSON>, who told the panel the inner workings of La Cosa Nostra. Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., said he will hold three more hearings, so the panel can assess the state of organized crime 25 years after <PERSON> Valachi </PERSON>'s testimony Monday's most dramatic testimony came from <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON>, who spoke in Italian and had his words translated for the committee. <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> has testified previously for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Italian governments and helped convict nearly 500 mobsters, most in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON>, two of his top aides, and <PERSON> Keeney </PERSON> all told the senators that law enforcement officials have severely damaged organized crime _ in part through new statutes and partly because the code of silence is now often broken. <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> gave some insight on why this has happened. `` Over the years, I have seen our organization change from within,'' <PERSON> Buscetta </PERSON> testified. `` I have seen money, drugs, and greed corrupt and destroy the Cosa Nostra code of honor and loyalty to the families. `` I began to realize that drugs had changed everything, the family loyalties and codes of respect that I had known as a Mafioso were quickly becoming things of the past.'' Sessions testified: `` Omerta ... has been broken in recent years. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> has not only secured the cooperation and testimony of numerous individuals who have been utilized by the <ORGANIZATION> LCN </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cosa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nostra </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- to promote their criminal activities but has elicited the cooperation of four <ORGANIZATION> LCN </ORGANIZATION> members whose knowledge and testimony ... has enabled the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to expand the attack on this national criminal enterprise.'' He identified the four as <PERSON> Aladena </PERSON> <PERSON> Frattiano </PERSON>, the former acting boss of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> LCN family; <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lonardo </PERSON>, the former underboss of the <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> organized crime family; and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Giorno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Caramandi </PERSON>, a capo -LRB- lieutenant -RRB- and soldier respectively in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> family. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> executive assistant director <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Revell </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said Mafia families in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have not taken over the drug trade, although individual organized-crime members are involved with narcotics. `` There's a change in <ORGANIZATION> LCN </ORGANIZATION> membership,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, deputy assistant <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> director in the criminal investigative division. `` Where there is money to be made, members of <ORGANIZATION> LCN </ORGANIZATION> will become involved in anything.'' <PERSON> Revell </PERSON> also told the committee that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> believes it knows who is responsible for the disappearance of former <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union head <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffa </PERSON> on July 30, 1975. <PERSON> Revell </PERSON> did not name them, but said they are in prison on other charges. <PERSON> Revell </PERSON> said he doubted there would be enough evidence to bring them to trial. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> on earlier occasions has asserted that it believed it knew who killed <PERSON> Hoffa </PERSON>. An <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> memo suggested <PERSON> Hoffa </PERSON>'s disappearance was linked to <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> `` Tony Pro'' <PERSON> Provenzano </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> boss and reputed organized crime captain imprisoned on a racketeering conviction. <PERSON> Provenzano </PERSON> has denied he was involved.
