 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has relinquished his duties temporarily following major surgery for removal of a malignant tumor, a newspaper reported today. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, 62, underwent surgery March 25 for removal of a tumor, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted an unidentified <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T spokesman as saying. The tumor was malignant and <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> is undergoing chemotherapy as an outpatient, the spokesman said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief operating officer, has taken charge. The spokesman said it was too soon to determine how long <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> would need to recover. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, a 44-year employee with the telecommunications giant, has served as its chairman and chief executive since 1986. He began his career cleaning dirt from telephone manholes and eventually rose through several management jobs at other <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> companies before becoming president of <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>. He moved to <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T headquarters in 1977.
