<FIRST>r a PM-BabyHearts     04-12 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Hearts,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anencephalic Donor Program Temporarily Halted; Baby's Respirator
Removed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A hospital suspended its largely unsuccessful effort to harvest organs for transplants from infants born with most of their brains missing, as doctors took the sixth such baby off life support. Ten-day-old <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovette </PERSON> <PERSON> Mount </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, was removed from life support Monday and will be allowed to die, spokesman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Schafer </PERSON> said by telephone from <ORGANIZATION> Loma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, 60 miles east of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON> said that while <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> plans to maintain five to seven more anencephalic babies on life support so they can be used as organ donors, the hospital wo n't do so until it modifies its existing guidelines for use of such infants, who are born with most of their brains missing. The review will be completed within two weeks, he said, refusing to elaborate on the planned changes. <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON>'s program was aimed at maintaining anencephalic babies on respirators for seven days or until they were declared brain-dead, whichever came first. Anencephalic babies inevitably die within days to weeks. The idea was to maintain them on life support so their organs would n't deteriorate as they died. The seven-day limit was established to counter criticism that the doomed babies were being kept alive _ and suffering _ indefinitely merely to save the lives of other babies needing donated organs. A <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> infant identified only as <PERSON> Baby </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> was the only one of the six anencephalic babies maintained on life support at <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Linda </LOCATION> to be declared brain-dead within the seven-day limit. But a suitable recipient for his heart and other organs could not be found. None of the five others were suitable for donations of major organs, although heart valves and corneas were transplanted from some of them. <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> surgeons did transplant an anencephalic's heart into <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Holc </PERSON>, the son of a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> couple, last Oct. 16. But that heart came from a baby girl who was maintained on life support in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, not at <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Linda </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, who received his new heart three hours after his birth by Caesarean section, was the world's youngest transplant recipient. He has been released from the hospital and physicians said recently he was doing well. <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> triggered a major medical controversy in 1984 when Dr. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> implanted a baboon's heart in a girl known as <PERSON> Baby </PERSON> <PERSON> Fae </PERSON>, who was born with a fatally underdeveloped heart and died 20 -LCB- days after the transplant. Since then, the hospital turned toward anencephalic babies as possible organ donors for infants with fatal heart defects.
