<HEAD>Contras Agree To Resume Technical Talks On Peace Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nicaraguan rebels agreed to a call from the leftist Sandinista government to resume technical talks on a cease-fire plan that had stalled over arms shipments to the U.S.-supported Contras. In another development, the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> received a fresh supply of newsprint from the government on Monday and said it would resume publication today for the first time since April 5. <PERSON> Cristiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> assistant director, said the paper received 42 tons of newsprint from the government-owned monopoly at mid-day Monday, too late for <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> editors to put out an afternoon edition. <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> had attributed the cutoff of newsprint to `` discrimination of the government.'' It noted that Barricada, the Sandinista party mouthpiece, and the pro-government <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuevo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diario </ORGANIZATION> continued to publish without interruption. The Nicaraguan Resistance, the main Contra umbrella group, on Monday night said it will send a delegation to the southern town of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> on Wednesday to resume the talks. There was no immediate reaction from the government. Earlier Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> proposed that the talks be held Wednesday or Thursday and suggested the Contras send an advance team to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> to prepare for high-ranking political discussions scheduled for Friday. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> released a statement proposing the technical talks resume at noon Wednesday in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. Top-level Contra leaders will travel to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Friday to continue the peace negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> based on progress at the <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> talks, the statement said. `` The high level commission composed of members of the directorate will arrive in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> April 15 subject to the work of the special commission,'' it said. The statement added that <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON>, secretary of the resistance directorate, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadhagen </PERSON>, another Contra representative, will arrive in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Thursday to work out the agenda for the high-level meeting. Last Friday, military commanders of the two sides suspended negotiations on defining how the Contras are to gather in cease-fire zones in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The meetings ended after the Contras asked for a recess of several days to discuss a 25-point government plan. The talks are called for in the March 23 cease-fire agreement reached by Sandinista and Contra leaders in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. Under terms of the plan, <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas were to gather at the zones during the first 15 days of April. A provisional 60-day cease-fire went into effect April 1. In six days of discussions, both sides agreed on seven zones but failed to define the operating conditions and security measures. A 34-point <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> proposal would allow the rebels to maintain munitions in the zones. It also would prohibit the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> from receiving any military aid from the Soviet bloc. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichler </PERSON>, an American lawyer negotiating for the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>, described those two points as `` absolutely unacceptable.'' The cease-fire plan would permit the Contras to receive only food and basic supplies channeled through a neutral organization. Political leaders of both sides had been scheduled to meet last Wednesday in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> but the rebels postponed the meeting, saying the technical talks in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> had not advanced enough to move toward political issues. The rebels also have said they will not continue the high-level political talks unless they are free to meet with opposition leaders in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. The government maintains that the peace agreement specifies Contra representation in politics begins only after the rebels move into the cease-fire zones.
