<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Killings,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Pleased With Revocation Of Amnesty In Slaying Of Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> applauded a decision by President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> that revoked an amnesty for three men charged in the 1985 slaying of six Americans. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> cited an international treaty as the legal basis for denying amnesty to the three suspects, said <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdivieso </PERSON>, the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Martial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, who announced the decision Monday. `` On the issue of amnesty, it has been the position of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government that this attack on innocent unarmed persons should not go unpunished,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McManus </PERSON>. `` We welcome President <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s decision to forward the case to the courts where evidence can be brought and a decision rendered.'' Thirteen people were killed on June 19, 1985, when assailants wearing Salvadoran ary uniforms opened fire with automatic weapons on patrons at two outdoor cafes in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Among the dead were four off-duty Marines and two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businessmen. The Marines, who were guards at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, wore civilian clothes and sat at two tables with other young people when the attackers drove up. A little-known leftist group, the <ORGANIZATION> Mardoqueo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cruz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guerrilla </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commandos </ORGANIZATION>, claimed responsibility for the killings. The group is an offshoot of one of the five guerrilla armies that form the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, which has been fighting the U.S.-backed Salvadoran government for eight years. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Melendez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Dimas </PERSON> <PERSON> Aguilar </PERSON> are charged with helping plan the `` Pink Zone massacre,'' named after the fashionable district of shops and restaurants where the killings occurred. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolanos </PERSON> is the only one of the three the government alleges was among the gunmen. None of the three has been tried. Eight other people, who are fugitives, allegedly took part in the crime. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s government decreed a broad amnesty in November 1987 as part of a regional peace accord. About 450 people were freed under the measure, which applied to those convicted or accused of politically motivated crimes. When the Martial Court, the country's highest military tribunal, ruled in January that the three men should receive amnesty, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government called the decision `` morally mistaken and politically damaging.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> later approved a measure that calls for withholding 10 percent of appropriated economic aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> if the suspects are freed. The three were kept in jail pending <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s review of the case. A lower court military judge had ruled the three should be covered by the amnesty because their alleged crime was politically motivated. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, as commander-in-chief of the armed forces, is empowered to review the Martial Court's decision. The treaty cited by <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, the Convention on the Prevention and <ORGANIZATION> Punishment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crimes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internationally </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protected </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION>, was ratified by <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in 1980. `` According to the president, the treaty takes precedence over the amnesty law,'' <PERSON> Valdivieso </PERSON> told reporters. Lawyer <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Portillo </PERSON>, representing the suspects, said he has not decided whether to appeal the case to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. He called <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s reasoning `` arbitrary.'' The amnesty program was part of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s compliance with a Central American peace plan signed in August 1987 by <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> and the presidents of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. About one-third of those freed under the program were leftist guerrillas. Another third were accused or convicted of crimes, including murder and torture, by rightist organizations. The political leanings of the other third was unclear. Two former national guardsmen convicted in the 1981 murders of two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> land reform advisers were freed under the amnesty. Five national guardsmen convicted in the 1980 murders of four American churchwomen were not covered by the measure.
