<HEAD>Hearing Begins Into Blood Test Not Allowed in Criminal Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A type of blood test barred as evidence in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> criminal trials is on trial itself this week, as supporters seek to overturn the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 1986 ruling declaring it inadmissible. Prosecutors from <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> counties claim electrophoresis has been refined since the high court's decision. Attorneys representing two defendants against whom test results could be applied deny the prosecutors' claims. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s 1986 ruling came on a 3-2 decision with two justices not taking part. Since then, one of the justices in the majority _ former Chief Justice <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mennen </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> _ has died and has been replaced by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>. In an unusual arrangement, Circuit Judges <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kent </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> began taking testimony Monday in a joint evidentiary hearing. Assistant prosecutors <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Molen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kent </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> are seeking decisions from the judges allowing use of electrophoresis tests as evidence in stabbing cases they are handling. <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Molen </PERSON> is prosecuting a case against <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>, 26, charged with two counts of assault with intent to murder. <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> is prosecuting <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoughton </PERSON>, 21, charged with two counts of first-degree murder in the deaths of two people in <LOCATION> Taylor </LOCATION>. `` We think the -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- decision was a mistake and we hope to correct it,'' <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Molen </PERSON> said before Monday's hearing began. But <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON>'s attorney, said he does n't think the test has been accepted generally by scientists for use in criminal trials. `` I think the prosecution and the prosecution community want to change the ruling,'' he said. `` There's been a change in the -LRB- Supreme -RRB- court. ... It's not that there has been a scientific advancement.'' Electrophoresis is a process to separate molecules of a substance by their electrical charge. It has been used in genetic testing, identification of certain enzymes in a variety of organs and in analysis of DNA, which carries genetic characteristics. The hearing is expected to last a week and should involve detailed scientific testimony about proteins, enzymes and `` markers'' they leave in dried blood. <PERSON> Vander </PERSON> <PERSON> Molen </PERSON> said use of the test in his case against <PERSON> Tanner </PERSON> is not critical. But, he said: `` We've got nearly 10 cases in which we need this test. This kind of evidence is important in the most serious of cases.''
