<FIRST>r a PM-PainConference     04-12 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pain Conference,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Gather for Pain Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Describing an ache may be easy to the sufferer, but to pain researchers the feeling of hurt is complex almost beyond description. Researchers at a four-day international `` Pain Measurement'' conference that began Monday are trying to develop a unified theory for the study of pain. The conference is sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> and funded by a grant from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. One in three people in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> suffers from chronic pain and millions are routinely incapacitated by it, but medical science often can do little to to prevent or effectively treat recurrent pain, because patients are suffering from something that ca n't be seen, felt or observed by someone else. The subjective and intangible nature of pain frustrates many people involved in its research. `` The problem with the meaning of the word pain has been around since <PERSON> Aristotle </PERSON>,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeser </PERSON>, a neurosurgeon and director of the university's Multidisciplinary Pain Center. `` How do you go about measuring pain?'' <PERSON> Loeser </PERSON> asks. `` We're not very far along in the clinical setting. It's too complex a phenomenon.'' Only within about the last two decades has the problem of pain gained serious attention in medical research, in large part because of the pioneering efforts of Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonica </PERSON>, chairman emeritus of the school's department of anesthesiology. <PERSON> Bonica </PERSON>'s work on the management of pain, which emphasizes a comprehensive approach rather than hit-and-miss drug therapies, paved the way for the serious study of pain. `` Everybody measures pain in a different way,'' said <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, a psychopharmacologist in pain research at the university and the independent <ORGANIZATION> Fred </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutchinson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` We do n't at present have a theory, a single theory, that everyone agrees upon,'' said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. Pain measurement research generally relies on laboratory tests of animals, lab tests on humans or studies of patient care, each with its own accepted methods for measuring and defining pain. None completely translates into an acceptable method for the other. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> said pain often is taken seriously by medical professionals only when tissue damage can be identified, although a lot of chronic pain apparently exists without any identifiable tissue damage. Some researchers try to measure this kind of pain by analyzing behavior or looking at brain waves and other electrical signals. Those dealing with humans ask the sufferer to describe the hurt, `` but how can you tell if an infant, who ca n't yet speak, is experiencing pain?'' asked <PERSON> Loeser </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> researchers expect a good deal of argument and contention at the conference. In fact, they deliberately scheduled scientists with opposing views to speak in succession. About 60 researchers are expected to attend. `` It's my belief that we can bring this all together if we can find a uniform theory for pain,'' said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. `` When we have reached it, our power to solve the perplexities of pain scientifically and to control the human and animal suffering that it causes will be greatly increased.''
</TEXT>
