<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s key stock market indicator closed today at an all-time high and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar climbed in trading against the Japanese yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained 175.98 points Monday, added another 5.97 points, or 0.02 percent, to close at 26,930.84. On Monday, the stock market's key barometer briefly touched a new high of 26,998.36 points during the morning trading, but then fell back. Boosted by the steady dollar and a strong Monday showing on Wall Street, the Nikkei index soared again today to 26,976.21 points minutes after the start of trading. Then profit-taking set in, indicating `` the market was rising too high -LRB- and -RRB- eased share prices a little in the afternoon,'' said <PERSON> Tadaaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Uehara </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Wako </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. However, the index rose again in the market's last hour, led by blue chip electricals, <PERSON> Uehara </PERSON> said. Many investors were encouraged by the dollar's stability and felt the electricals would continue to benefit from the stable dollar, traders said. Other popular issues included precision machineries, drugs and constructions. Losers included chemicals, securities and real estates. Volume on the first section trade was estimated at a moderate 750 million shares, down from 900 million shares Monday. On the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> foreign exchange market, meanwhile, the dollar closed at 126.50 yen, up 0.79 yen from its close Monday of 125.71 yen and up also from its opening today of 126.40 yen. `` It appears the dollar has stabilized at what it should be,'' said a foreign exchange dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. Trading was mixed in dollar-buying and selling, with a strong wait-and-see attitude among participants regarding this week's meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of monetary authorities from seven majo