<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature approved a new Cabinet today that includes younger members more closely tied to economic reforms of senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>. The 2,859 delegates of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> also passed constitutional amendments sanctioning private businesses and the right to transfer use of land. Delegates confirmed 41 ministerial posts, named three vice premiers and appointed nine as state councilors to the State Council, or Cabinet. They also trimmed the council as part of government efforts to become more efficient, eliminating posts for two vice premiers, two state councilors and four ministers. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON>, 60, who has been vice foreign minister in charge of relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, succeeded <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xueqian </PERSON> as foreign minister, while Gen. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiwei </PERSON>, 74, a member of the Politburo and head of the <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION>, took over the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> from ailing <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Aiping </PERSON>, 78. The three vice premiers who will serve under Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> are outgoing Foreign Minister <PERSON> Wu </PERSON>, 67, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilin </PERSON>, 71, and <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiyun </PERSON>, 59. <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> previously served as vice premiers. Ten of the 41 ministers are new, as are seven of the nine state councilors. The average age of the premier, vice premiers and nine councilors dropped from 67 to 61. The state councilors include people closely identified with <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s economic reforms and policy of opening to the outside world, such as new <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Tieying </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Xitong </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Junsheng </PERSON>, who also retained his post of secretary general of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. One constitutional amendment guarantees the rights and interests of the 21.5 million Chinese now working in 13.7 million private businesses. Private entrepreneurs, operating small food and clothing stalls and restaurants, now account for almost 13 percent of the nation's total retail sales. The other amendment, also tied to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s policy of giving greater flexibility to its economy, states that `` the right to the use of land may be transferred according to law.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has experimented with transfer of land-use rights as part of efforts to provide land to more ambitious farmers and accelerate urban development. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign policy is not expected to change under <PERSON> Qian </PERSON>, a career diplomat who spent 10 years in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and has headed China-Soviet normalization talks since 1982. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON>, who also has been <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s spokesman on disarmament issues, speaks English and Russian. Under Wu, foreign minister since November 1982, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has maintained a course of neutrality in superpower disputes, increased economic and political ties with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, eased tensions with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and championed Third World causes. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiwei </PERSON>, a close confidante of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> who served under <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> in the wars against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the Nationalists, is expected to lead efforts to restore the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s authority over the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Among other major appointments, Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> took over the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Restructuring </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for setting guidelines for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s market-oriented reforms. Vice Premier <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilin </PERSON> was confirmed as head of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, newly created out of two commissions. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> are both regarded as more cautious than party head <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> toward reforms designed to substitute central planning with market-determined production. Their leadership over the two key economic commissions could slow down the pace of new reform initiatives in coming years. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Senmao </PERSON>, 58, was named railways minister to succeed <PERSON> Ding </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangen </PERSON>, who was forced to resign last month following a string of fatal accidents. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> has been vice minister since 1982. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Guixian </PERSON>, a Soviet-trained engineer who was party chief in <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION> province, was named governor of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION>, succeeding <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhua </PERSON>, one of the highest-ranking women in the government.
</TEXT>
