<FIRST>r i PM-China-Profiles     04-12 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Profiles,0850</SECOND>
<BYLINE>With PM-China-Congress
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are brief sketches of some of the new members of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Cabinet appointed today by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Qin Jiwei</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Qin </PERSON>, a veteran general and protege of senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, is expected to increase the ministry's role in making military decisions, long handled by the party. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON>, 74, commander of the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Military Region, is a veteran of the 1934-35 Long March, the Communist forces' epic retreat during the Chinese civil war. In 1946-49 he served as an army officer under <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s command and later commanded troops in the Korean War. He replaces the ailing <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Aiping </PERSON>, 80. Real power in the military, however, long has resided in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, headed by <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> has been deliberately kept weak since 1971, when then-Defense Minister <PERSON> Lin </PERSON> <PERSON> Biao </PERSON> allegedly plotted a coup against <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>. Western military analysts believe the leadership plans to reduce the party's military role to setting overall policy and strengthen the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> as part of its efforts to make the military more professional and modern. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> was born in 1914 in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hubei </LOCATION> province, and joined the party in 1930. He was purged during the far-leftist Cultural Revolution that began in 1966, and was rehabilitated in 1973.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Qian Qichen</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Qian </PERSON>, 60, is a career diplomat who has headed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s border talks with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and had been vice foreign minister since 1982. He succeeds <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xueqian </PERSON>, who was promoted to vice premier. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON>, who speaks English and <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION>, studied in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from 1954 to 1955 and was second secretary and counselor at the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in the 1960s. He spent a total of 10 years in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> from 1954 to 1974, according to his official biography. In 1974, he became ambassador to <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guinea-Bissau </LOCATION> in northwest <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. He returned to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to become head of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. When <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> began talks with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1982 over their disputed border, <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> was appointed to head negotiations. After 11 rounds, neither side has reported significant progress. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> was born in the northeast industrial city of <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION> in 1928 and joined the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1942. He worked for the party's underground while reporting for the <ORGANIZATION> Ta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pao </ORGANIZATION> newspaper in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> during the 1040s. He is a member of the party's policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>People's Bank of China Governor Li Guixian</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, a provincial party leader with little experience in finance, was the surprise choice to fill the difficult post of governor of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION>, the country's central bank. The 50-year-old <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, a Soviet-trained engineer who since 1986 has been party secretary in <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>, also became one of nine state councilors named by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He succeeds <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhua </PERSON>, 67, one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most visible and powerful women politicians, who had held the post for three years. <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> was elected vice chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> takes over the bank at a critical stage as it tries to change from exercising administrative control over the banking system to adopting indirect controls through interest rates and credit. It also is promoting interbank markets, making greater use of bonds and foreign credit to finance <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s development and trying to rein in excessive growth in money supply. <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Liaoning </LOCATION> province, spent about five years in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> beginning in 1960 studying electric vacuum chemistry. After returning to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, he worked in the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> and between 1967 and 1976 was a technician, deputy director and chief engineer of a large factory. He later was chief engineer of the <ORGANIZATION> Liaoning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Provincial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, deputy governor of <LOCATION> Liaoning </LOCATION>, and in 1985 became party secretary of the northeastern province.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Railways Minister Li Senmao</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Li </PERSON> faces the daunting task of resolving problems of aging equipment and sloppy discipline that have contributed to four fatal train accidents this year. <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, 58, became vice minister of the <ORGANIZATION> Railways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 and has been acting foreign minister since early March. It is his first Cabinet post. <PERSON> Ding </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s predecessor, resigned in disgrace to take responsibility for three train accidents in January, which killed a total of 141 people. A few weeks later, 28 people were killed in the fourth accident, the collision of two passenger trains in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. Investigations revealed deep-seated problems in the Railways Ministry's administration, including the lack of a safety control system, serious overloading of trains, outdated equipment, loose discipline, poor worker training and frequent thefts of railway materials. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s 12th <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> but was downgraded last October to an alternate membership in the policy-making body when it was reduced from 210 members to 175.
</TEXT>
