<HEAD>Dollar Little Changed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was little changed against most major foreign currencies in light European trading early today. Gold prices rose. Dealers said they expected the dollar to trade within a narrow range before Wednesday's meeting of finance ministers from the seven major industrialized democracies and the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for February on Thursday. Few traders predicted any sharp improvement in the merchandise trade deficit from January's shortfall of $ 12.44 billion. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose to a closing 126.50 Japanese yen from 125.71 yen at Monday's close. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it edged up to 126.53 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday: _ 1.6853 West German marks, down from 1.6855 _ 1.3957 Swiss francs, up from 1.3953 _ 5.7180 French francs, up from 5.7145 _ 1.8897 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8910 _ 1,249.75 Italian lire, up from 1,249.50 _ 1.2390 Canadian dollars, unchanged In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.848 Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 450.50 a troy ounce, up from $ 449.50 bid late Monday. At mid-morning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 450.20. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 450.20, up from $ 449.00 bid late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose to a closing bid of $ 452.21 from $ 451.95 at Monday's close. Silver bullion rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a bid price of $ 6.44 a troy ounce, up from a $ 6.42 bid late Monday.
