<FIRST>r a PM-MissingAtSea     04-12 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing At Sea,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shrimper Describes 12-Day Ordeal in Gulf of Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRYSTAL RIVER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A boater who spent 12 days drifting in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> without food or water wanted to see his 5-year-old daughter before he died, but perished hours before rescuers arrived, said a friend who survived. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, 19, describing the ordeal shared by him and <PERSON> Jimmie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Thacker </PERSON> from his hospital bed in this Gulf Coast city on Monday, said he had daydreams about grape soda and ice cream while adrift. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, who was rescued Saturday, was in stable condition today after being moved out of the intensive care unit at <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rivers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. He was being treated for hypothermia, sunburn, starvation and dehydration, said a nursing supervisor who asked that her name not be used. <PERSON> Thacker </PERSON>, 25, died late Friday or early Saturday. `` All I know is that he wanted to see his little girl again before he died,'' said <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, a shrimper. <PERSON> Thacker </PERSON> was separated from his wife and 5-year-old girl, who live in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The ordeal began March 28, when <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thacker </PERSON> went to Anclote Key, an island north of <LOCATION> Tarpon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, in a 14-foot skiff with two friends. At dusk, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thacker </PERSON> left the island to get matches and more soft drinks. They never came back. Their friends got back to the mainland the next morning by hitching a ride from a passing fisherman and told family members about the disappearence, prompting a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> search the next day. The searchers gave up a week later. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said the shore was out of sight when the boat lost power. They drifted south and west, and lost their bearings. All he and <PERSON> Thacker </PERSON> had to drink were two bottles of <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>, which they emptied the first night so they could use them to bail out the boat after it was drenched by 16-foot waves. `` I did n't use my head. I freaked out,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. `` I could have used the engine cover'' to bail. Desperate for water, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> daydreamed and used saltwater to rinse his mouth. He said he spent much of his time praying. On several occasions, porpoises came to the boat and lifted their snouts, apparently to see if the men had any fish for them. `` Seeing the porpoises made me feel better,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. When they had been adrift for several days, a big shrimp boat came into view. Believing help had finally come, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> picked up the engine box and began waving it frantically to get the other boat's attention `` I was yelling and hollering at the top of my lungs and everything,'' he said. But the other boat did n't approach. `` It just kept going,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. `` One person on board raised his hand and waved as the boat pulled away.'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> was rescued when a charter boat spotted him 14 miles west of <LOCATION> Crystal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Despite his experience, he said he's looking forward to getting back to work on the Gulf. `` It's my home away from home,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. `` It's how I make my living.''
