<SECOND>PM-Polygamist Trial,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Testimony Begins Today In Polygamist Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Trial scheduled to start at 11:30 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mostly Mormon jury will sit in judgment of four members of a renegade polygamist clan charged in the bombing of a Mormon chapel and the subsequent 13-day standoff with police. Federal prosecutors plan to call at least 150 witnesses, including a Mormon bishop, neighbors of the defendants and reporters, in the high-profile case beginning today. Defense lawyers, however, are n't sure it can be judged fairly. Attorney <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Metos </PERSON>, asked if the 12 jurors seated Friday, truly were the defendants' peers, responded, `` They have no peers.'' A <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> correction officer was killed in an exchange of gunfire at the end of the siege. The <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> attorney general's office plans to file homicide charges as soon as the federal trial ends, said Associate Attorney General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>. The trial will be one of the most closely followed in recent memory in a state with an estimated 30,000 members of polygamist families. Most coexist peacefully with their Mormon neighbors, who make up nearly 70 percent of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s population. The <ORGANIZATION> Mormon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> renounced polygamy in 1890 and now excommunicates advocates and practitioners of multiple-wife marriages. The four defendants include <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, 44, mother of seven and widow of slain polygamist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, who was gunned down in 1979 by police serving a contempt citation at the same farm where his family held authorities at bay while awaiting the dead patriarch's resurrection. Law enforcement officers believe Mrs. Singer was the brains behind the bombing and standoff, while her son-in-law, <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, provided the muscle. According to Mrs. <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>'s diary, submitted as evidence during pretrial hearings, <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> and two others planted the bomb at the <ORGANIZATION> Kamas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION> on Jan. 16 as the Singer women prayed at the family home two miles away. <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 27, and Mrs. Singer are charged with seven and eight counts, respectively, in a nine-count indictment that was handed up shortly after their arrests. It was reduced last week to eight counts when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> dismissed a conspiracy charge. Charged with four counts each are <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, 21, <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s brother, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, Mrs. Singer's 21-year-old wheelchair-bound son. Singer is state authorities' prime suspect in the slaying of the corrections officer. All four defendants are charged with the attempted killing of <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents during the standoff, assault on federal officers and two firearms violations. Mrs. Singer and <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> are charged additionally with using an explosive to damage the chapel, use of a bomb and possession of a bomb. Mrs. Singer also faces one count of possession of a sawed-off shotgun. In telephone calls to news organizations shortly after the bombing, Mrs. Singer and <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> said the blast was symbolic of the `` collapse of the church, state and nation'' that would occur with the second coming of Christ and the return of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>. Clan members contend Singer's death was the result of a `` government-church conspiracy'' and a `` long train of abuse'' against the family. <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>'s attorneys asked that the trial be moved out of state, arguing their client could not receive a fair hearing in Mormon-dominated <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. While <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> has not ruled on the motion, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, said Monday the case probably would not be transferred once the trial begins. <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Metos </PERSON>, representing <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, said the pool of 170 prospective jurors that reported for possible court duty last week was 90 percent Mormon.
