<HEAD>Thais Deny Weapons Smuggled On Hijacked Plane In Bangkok</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An investigator today ruled out the possibility that the hijackers of a Kuwaiti airliner smuggled their weapons on board the plane in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> through a ramp area used by service personnel. The possibility was raised on Monday by <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON>, head of security for the Montreal-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The Kuwaiti jet was carrying 112 people when it was hijacked April 5 on a flight from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and forced down in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The hijackers, who are armed with grenades and handguns, later forced the plane to <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, where they have killed two of the approximately 50 passengers they are still holding hostage. `` It is not possible,'' Group Capt. <PERSON> Anake </PERSON> <PERSON> Udit </PERSON> said today when asked about <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON>' theory. <PERSON> Anake </PERSON>, a deputy managing director of the Airports Authority of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, is a member of a team investigating what happened during the 15 hours the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet was on the ground in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. `` Anyone going through the ramp area had to go through tough security clearance,'' <PERSON> Anake </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` That is not easy.'' On Monday, <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> said: `` On the basis of discussions we've had so far, the probability is that weapons were placed on board the aircraft through the coercion or collusion of staff on the ramp.'' The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> is an international association of commercial airlines. <PERSON> Anake </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> hires guards from the airport authority and from a private security firm to guard its planes while in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. `` The security men do not take their eyes off the plane once it landed,'' he said. <PERSON> Anake </PERSON> said the airport authority has not discussed the origin of the weapons with the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` We expected suppositions like this and we're saying -LRB- the weapons -RRB- did n't come from here.'' Thai investigators have theorized that the weapons were smuggled aboard before the plane reached <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> on April 4 from <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. They said the hijackers may have left the weapons on board during the stop. On the possible coercion or collusion of staff on the ramp, <PERSON> Anake </PERSON> said: `` It was more likely they -LRB- the hijackers -RRB- used their own people.'' He said airport authority investigators were questioning about 100 people, including guards of the private security company and airport authority personnel, including cleaners, mechanics, engineers and employees of the <ORGANIZATION> Bangkok </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Anake </PERSON> said he could not say when the probe would be completed. A separate investigation team is headed by Interior Minister <PERSON> Prachuab </PERSON> <PERSON> Suntrangkoon </PERSON>.
