 A series of explosions and a fire at an oil field supply manufacturing plant early today forced the evacuations of nearby residents, authorities said. Two plant employees suffered minor injuries, and were treated and released at a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> hospital. The explosion was at the <ORGANIZATION> Owens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tool </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, located between <PERSON> Godley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cresson </PERSON>, about 25 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. Authorities said they ordered the evacuations of about 30 people from a square mile of the mostly rural area around the plant because they believed 20,000 to 30,000 pounds of explosives were stored in the area. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, the plant's owner, said a charge being manufactured for use in oil drilling operations exploded, triggering other explosions and a fire. The plant was destroyed, he said. Firefighters from several surrounding towns, and volunteers battled the blaze, but were pulled back at times because of fears of possible additional explosions. The evacuees were taken to the <ORGANIZATION> Godley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, where they were told to wait until it was safe to return home.
