<HEAD>Archbishop Defends His Activism Against Criticism From Botha</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WINDHOEK </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ In a stinging rebuke to President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> today denied that he endorsed Marxism and said his fight against apartheid was deeply rooted in Christian tradition. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, the first black to lead the Anglican Church in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, released the text of a letter to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> defending his challenges of government policy in a church-state confrontation that has intensified over the past two months. The Nobel Peace Prize laureate was responding to a March letter from <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> in which the South African president suggested <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> was furthering the cause of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement and promoting a Marxist dictatorship. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, whose letter was quoted at length on South African television, asked whether <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> was acting `` on behalf of the kingdom of God or the kingdom promised by the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>.'' Replied <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>: `` I work for God's kingdom. For whose kingdom, with your apartheid policy, do you work for?'' `` I reject atheistic Marxism and I reject apartheid, which I find equally abhorrent,'' said <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>. He cited numerous scriptural passages to support his contention that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s policy of racial separation is `` unbiblical, un-Christian, immoral and evil.'' Referring to insinuations in <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s letter, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said he had never listened to the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s radio broadcasts or read its magazine. `` My theological position derives from the Bi