<HEAD>Whale Sighted In Delaware, 70 Miles from Sea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with today's search, picking up
at the 3rd graf previous, and Deletes the now redundant 8th graf
previous, beginning ``Officials were unable.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Teams from several state and federal agencies searched today for a whale that swam about 70 miles up the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, attracting flocks of boaters despite warnings it could damage small craft. The 40-foot whale, first reported by a tugboat crew, was last seen just before nightfall Monday at the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> Memorial Bridge, which crosses the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> about 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, officials said. Personnel from <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> marine police, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> went out in boats after daybreak to try to find and identify the marine mammal, said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamison </PERSON>, a public information officer with the natural resources department. `` It's such a gray day here that it's not going to be easy to spot it,'' Ms. <PERSON> Jamison </PERSON> said. The search crews hoped to guide the whale, of undetermined species, back out to sea, she said. The last time a live whale was seen so far up the heavily industrialized <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> was in 1890, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON>, a nationally recognized whale expert who directs the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mammal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stranding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Brigantine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` It could be sick; it could be an old animal dying; it could have been hit by a boat and dazed,'' <PERSON> Schoelkopf </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> was concerned both with the