<TEXT>
 Irish nationalist leader <PERSON> Dessie </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hare </PERSON> and four other men accused of kidnapping and maiming a wealthy dentist entered guilty pleas today as their trial began. The five had been expected to plead innocent. O'Hare limped into court. <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> police shot and seriously wounded him and killed a companion at a roadblock three weeks after police freed the dentist Nov. 5. The kidnappers had escaped in a hijacked van after a shootout with police. The guilty pleas followed two adjournments that delayed the proceedings at <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>'s anti-terrorist Special Criminal Court for an hour. Scores of armed police and soldiers were posted around the courthouse. An army helicopter hovered overhead when an armed convoy escorting the defendants arrived from a top-security prison in <LOCATION> Portlaoise </LOCATION>, 50 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>. The defendants each admitted to falsely imprisoning 38-year-old <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Grady </PERSON>. O'Hare also pleaded guilty to maliciously wounding <PERSON> O'Grady </PERSON> with intent to maim. Other lesser charges were dropped. There was no immediate explanation of why the guilty pleas were made. Prosecution and defense lawyers were expected to outline the pleas in proceedings later today. Sentencing was expected Wednesday. The kidnappers chopped off tips of two of <PERSON> O'Grady </PERSON>'s fingers during his 22 days in captivity, authorities said. He was freed by police after detectives chanced upon the gang in a <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> house on Nov. 5. Published reports said they had demanded a $ 2.5 million ransom, but police said nothing had been paid. <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>, 29, is from <LOCATION> Ballymacauley </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armagh </LOCATION>. Two other <LOCATION> No