<HEAD>100 Still Missing After Pakistani Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 100 people were still missing today, two days after an explosion at an ammunition depot killed 93 people and injured 1,100. State-run <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> television said 170 teams of explosives experts, working around the clock, have so far cleared 20,000 missiles, grenades and other weapons that lay around the twin cities of <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rawalpindi </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> said Monday that an estimated 6,500 devices were to be cleared. There was no explanation for the discrepancy in the figures. The <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today that agents from the pro-Soviet government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> were apparently responsible for Sunday's explosion. The newspaper, quoting unidentified sources, said Pakistani military experts had told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials about the cause of the blast. The explosion was caused by three incendiary devices carried to the ammunition dump by trucks bearing Afghan license plates and equipped with time fuses, the Times said. They were exploded in sequence, the newspaper said. Unidentified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sources told the newspaper the explosions wiped out a major source of CIA-supplied tactical assault weapons for resistance fighters battling the Soviet-backed government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. A four-man <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team of bomb disposal experts is helping to clear the unexploded ammunition, including some which fell on the residences of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> personnel and the international school. Television reports said most of the children missing from Sunday's blasts at the <LOCATION> Ojeri </LOCATION> army camp have been reunited with their families. About 100 people remained unaccounted for, it said. The Cabinet chaired by Prime Minister <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> met today to review the situation. Pakistani television said that during the Cabinet meeting, it was decided that a committee investigating the explosion should submit its findings with recommendations within 10 days and that they will be made public.
