<HEAD>Grateful Residents Offer Bride to Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grateful black residents who won a court battle against the government offered their white lawyer a bride, but he politely declined. `` I am very pleased to say that I already have a wife,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dugard </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Applied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witswatersrand </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. The community northwest of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> made the offer in keeping with tribal tradition. <PERSON> Dugard </PERSON> represented the 120,000-member community, Moutse, that was incorporated by the government into a homeland dominated by a different tribe on Jan. 1, 1986. The government's 10 homelands are part of a plan to grant limited autonomy to the country's blacks. They are not internationally recognized, however. A court ruled March 29 that President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> exceeded his powers when he incorporated <PERSON> Moutse </PERSON> into the <LOCATION> KwaNdebele </LOCATION> homeland. The community is independent of any homeland as a result of the decision. Most Moutse residents belong to the North Sotho tribe. They argued that their language and culture differed sharply from the <ORGANIZATION> Ndebeles </ORGANIZATION>, who make up most of <LOCATION> KwaNdebele </LOCATION>'s 400,000 people.
