<HEAD>33 Hurt as Chinese Rail Workers Assault Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of railway employees attacked train conducters with picks and stones after three co-workers were prevented from riding free, and 33 people were injured, it was reported Tuesday. The official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said five people remained in serious condition, and train windows were broken in the April 4 melee in southeastern <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> province. The attackers stripped the clothes of women conductors and kicked one pregnant conductor in the stomach, the newspaper reported. The workers used sticks to beat other employees and passengers who tried to protect them. The attack came after conductors refused to give free passage to three men who said they were railway employees but lacked identification. Railway employees are allowed free travel. The paper said the train was heading for <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION>, at the time. When it returned through the same area later in the day, 300 to 400 angry rail employees were waiting, the report said. The main attack took place at <LOCATION> Shaoguan </LOCATION>. When the train arrived at <LOCATION> Zheling </LOCATION>, a smaller station down the line, more attackers came aboard and continued the assault, the newspaper said. There was no mention of arrests.
