<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> scientist testified today that he knew of fraud taking place in research at the institute but was reluctant to report it because he feared retribution. Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Maplethorpe </PERSON>, who was conducting post-doctoral research at <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION>, said he learned of what he considered fraudulent research by <ORGANIZATION> Thereza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Imanishi-Kari </ORGANIZATION> but was reluctant to report it until just before receiving his degree. Dr. <PERSON> Maplethorpe </PERSON> said he told an <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION> official that he suspected fraud and the official's only action was to give him a form to fill out. `` I felt there was no question that if I made a formal charge of fraud it would not be taken seriously and I would be the person worst off for it,'' he said. Appearing today under subpoena before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on oversight and investigations, <PERSON> Maplethorpe </PERSON> said he was very reluctant to present the testimony and would not be there except for the legal compulsion. `` There is a tremendous disincentive to come forward and once they come forward, the instigators will pay a price,'' he said. The testimony came during hearings on practices of fraud in the government's $ 5-billion biomedical research program. In testimony before another subcommittee yesterday, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Feder </PERSON>, two <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> scientists, said they have received unfavorable job ratings since they have acted as whistleblowers about false research data reported by <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> grant recipients. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Feder </PERSON> said they began investigating allegations of misconduct by grant recipients about four years ago. Although <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> officially allows them to spend 20 percent of their time investigating scientific fraud, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said, he discovered in 1985 that his laboratory equipment at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diabetes </ORGANIZATION> and Digestive and Kidney Diseases had been removed and junked without notice. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Feder </PERSON>, whose work had always been judged satisfactory, said they began getting unfavorable job evaluations, which were reversed on appeal. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said their troubles clearly stemmed from their inquiries into fraudulent practices by <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> grant recipients. Another whistleblower who complained of mistreatment was Dr. <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobstein </PERSON>, who said `` I have been ignored by my friends, vilified by my enemies, despised, hated, condemned and on a rare but satisfying occasion, perhaps, respected.'' <PERSON> Jacobstein </PERSON> alleged that Dr. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Borer </PERSON>, a cardiologist and <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> professor, attempted to induce a student to make numerous misrepresentations in a joint scientific study report. He said <PERSON> Borer </PERSON> ultimately got away with a mild rebuke. <PERSON> Jacobstein </PERSON> estimated that although extreme forms of research fraud, such as wholesale fabrication of data, were `` fairly rare,'' an estimated 20 percent to 30 percent of research studies supported by <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> grants contained unethically flawed data. `` A scientist who cheats injures other scientists by misleading them, and he injures the public by wasting their money and sometimes by falsely claiming discoveries that directly affect the public health and welfare,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Feder </PERSON> said Monday in a joint statement to the subcommittee. Rep. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, chairman of the House Government Operations panel, expressed sympathy for a suggestion by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>, D-Mich., that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should approve criminal penalties for scientific fraud or misconduct because of its threat of `` incredible harm and injury to the public. The whistleblowers, who also included Professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprague </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Urbana-Champaign </ORGANIZATION>, complained that criminal penalties would be excessively harsh and might create a damaging climate of fear among scientists. The witnesses all expressed hope that the scientific community might find a way to improve internal safeguards against research abuses. But <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said no one _ neither the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION>, the universities receiving research grants nor professional scientific societies _ had shown willingness to solve the fraud problem.
