<FIRST>u w AM-Ozone-Packaging Bjt   04-12 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ozone-Packaging, Bjt,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozone-Destroying Chemicals To Be Gone From Food Containers Next
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Makers of plastic foam food containers will stop using ozone-destroying chemicals in their products after this year, the first industry to give up the compounds completely, their trade association said Tuesday. Major environmental groups and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> hailed the decision by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Foodservice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Packing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> as an important symbolic step in persuading others to find substitutes for the chlorofluorocarbon, or <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>, compounds. Consumers will notice little impact because the the decision does not mean an end to foam containers, valued for their lightness and insulating properties _ things like egg cartons and the clamshell hamburger containers used by fast-food chains. Two-thirds of those foams currently are made without CFCs. There are about 15 companies making the food packages, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bow </PERSON>, president of the institute, and more than a third of them have signed a letter pledging to give up CFCs by the end of the year. `` In 30 days we should have the rest of the industry'' signed up, <PERSON> Bow </PERSON> said. About 1.5 percent to 2 percent of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or 15 million pounds a year, goes to foam blowing agents for food packages, though 30 percent is used in blowing agents for other foams such as seat cushions and insulating panels. Gaseous CFCs are released into the atmosphere during the foam manufacturing process and some of the compounds also remain trapped in the foam, where they may be released into the environment later. For environmentalists, though, the food packages were a visible symbol of the threat to the Earth's protective ozone layer, and they already had persuaded some fast food chains _ and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> restaurant in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ not to use CFC-derived containers. Ozone at high altitudes protects the Earth from cancer-causing ultraviolet rays of the sun, but can be destroyed by chlorine liberated from the breakup of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds at those altitudes. Last month the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> reported that CFCs appear to have been responsible for an average 2.3 percent decline in the ozone shield at northern hemisphere mid-latitudes from 1969 to 1986. A treaty signed by 31 nations last fall requires a 50 percent cut in <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production by 1998. Most of the replacement for CFCs in foam packages is expected to be a related compound, HCFC-22, which has only 5 percent of the ozone-destroying ability of the chemicals being given up. The Natural Resources Defense Council, the Environmental Defense Fund and Friends of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> agreed to work with the packing institute in finding an eventual replacement for HCFC-22. All three groups praised the industry, and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> issued a statement praising the `` welcome contribution'' of less <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use as `` a model of cooperation between industry and the environmental community.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> said the announcement was even more significant than the <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement last month that it wanted to end <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production because <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> did not commit itself to a deadline the way the institute did. `` It is our intention to go to other sectors -LRB- of the economy -RRB- and say, ` These guys did it; so can you,''' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. Current non-CFC blowing agents, mostly volatile hydrocarbons like pentane, pose environmental threats of their own since these compounds help form ozone at low altitudes, where it is a pollutant. The substitute material costs 25 percent to 50 percent more than the compounds it replaces, but lasts longer, so costs will be increased little if at all, Bow said.
