<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese leaders on Tuesday elected a new cabinet in a vote that indicates a general support for <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>'s economic reforms although several conservatives received key posts <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON>, 60, a career diplomat who has been <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s chief negotiator with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, was elected as minister of Foreign Affairs, succeeding <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xueqian </PERSON>, 67. Gen. <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiwei </PERSON>, 74, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> and commander of the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Military Region, took over the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> from ailing <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Aiping </PERSON>, 78. Continuing an unprecedented movement started at the beginning of congress, delegates at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> actually voted against some of the cabinet candidates. In congresses past, all candidates were elected unanimously. The congress, which is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature, also passed two amendments to the constitution. One guarantees the rights of private businessmen, while the other recognizes the transfer of land-use rights, opening the way for the leasing of property. In voting by 2,859 delegates, the congress approved three vice premiers, nine state councillors and 41 ministers for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, or cabinet. The stress was on continuity, with the large majority of ministers either keeping their jobs or turning them over to people within their organizations. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> is headed by <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, 59, who was formally endorsed as premier earlier in the congress' annual session. Named as vice premiers were <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiyun </PERSON>, both returnees, and the outgoing foreign minister, <PERSON> Wu </PERSON>. The delegates were not given a choice in who they could pick for each office, although they could oppose the candidate or abstain from voting. The one surprise was the election of <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Guixian </PERSON>, a Soviet-trained engineer and party boss in <LOCATION> Anhui </LOCATION> province, to be governor of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION>, the central bank. <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, with no known financial background, will be responsible for the major task of reforming <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s inflexible banking system to allow interest rates to replace central planning in the management of the bank. According to New Evening Post a <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> daily, he received 404 opposing votes and 29 abstentions, more than any other candidate. As head of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Qin </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s confidantes, is expected to carry out <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s plan to mold the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> into a more powerful body. The ministry is now the weak sister to party and state military commissions both headed by <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>. Qian, the new foreign minister, is expected to follow closely the policies laid down by Wu, foreign minister since 1982. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in that period has steadily expanded economic and political ties with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> while gradually easing tensions with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> described the new government as `` a group of technocrats who are younger in age, pragmatic and enthusiastic in the reform.'' It said the average age of the cabinet dipped from 62 to 59 and that all but five members are college graduates. Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, a Soviet-trained engineer who is considered conservative when compared to <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, took over the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Restructuring </ORGANIZATION> the Economy. Senior Vice Premier <PERSON> Yao </PERSON>, who also wants to slow the pace of reform, was named head of the new <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. One constitutional amendment guarantees the rights and interests of the 21.5 million Chinese now engaged in 13.7 million private businesses. Private entrepreneurs, operating small food and clothing stalls and restaurants, now account for almost 13 percent of the nation's total retail sales. The other amendment, also tied to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s policy of giving greater flexibility to its economy, states that `` the right to the use of land may be transferred according to law.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has experimented with transfer of land-use rights as part of efforts to provide land to more ambitious farmers and accelerate urban development. The congress, which closes Wednesday, has been hailed as the most democratic in history, with delegates encouraged to speak out on such issues as inflation and faltering agricultural production.
