<HEAD>Committee Will Let Senate Decide on Mexican Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sharply divided <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> refused to slap <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> on Tuesday over its failings in the war on drugs, leaving that decision to the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where it could come to a vote in the next few days. The panel did approve a similar resolution condemning the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> for not doing enough to combat drug trafficking, and moved to add <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> to the list of countries that should come under increased scrutiny as drug producing or transit points. The vote on the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> issue was 10-6, and the <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> resolution passed on a voice vote. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> admnistration last month certified that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> are `` fully cooperating'' with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to halt drug trafficking. Such a certification is required for any foreign country identified as a drug producing or transit point to continue to receive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid and other benefits. But Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., objected to the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> certification, pointing to continued high rates of marijuana and cocaine flowing into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from that country and problems with official corruption and lack of cooperation with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug interdiction authorities <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> proposed a resolution to decertify <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, which could subject it to aid, lending and trade sanctions under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law. The Foreign Relations panel, after lengthy debate over the effect of such a move on overall <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, defeated an effort to send the bill to the floor with a favorable recommendation. The vote was an 8-8 tie, which defeated the motion under committee rules. In effect, the action left the decision to the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, since the bill has priority status and must go to the floor for final action in any case. But Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., who has been holding hearings on Latin American drug trafficking, said the move represented a victory in the war on drugs `` It reflects the changing mood and dynamic in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said, noting that several senators had switched sides on the issue in light of a growing awareness of the drug problem. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> predicted a hard-fought debate when the measure comes to the floor later this week or next week, and said he could not predict the outcome. The measure is primarily symbolic in its impact on foreign aid, since <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s only current <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid is $ 14.5 million in money to combat drugs, money which would be unaffected by any sanctions. More important for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, however, could be a requirement that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> oppose future loans from international development banks. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has a weighted vote in decisions on such loans, but not a majority. Decertification also could expose <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to various trade sanctions, at the discretion of the president. Arguing for the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> resolution, <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> noted that the administration itself had noted numerous failings by <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> when it certified full cooperation on March 1, noting that a `` higher level'' of cooperation was needed. `` You ca n't have it both ways,'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said. `` The point has really arrived where other countries are watching us,'' he said, noting that <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> ruler Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, indicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges, seems to be drawing strength from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> confusion over its policy toward him. But Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, D-Conn., said <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> already is devoting large proportions of its national budget to fighting drug trafficking and that decertification would destroy that cooperation `` They're doing a great deal,'' <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> said. `` This is a slap in the face that's going to set us in the wrong direction. ... If this resolution is adopted, you can expect the worst kind of cooperation.''
