<HEAD>Captives Swelter In Jumbo Prison, Waiting For Gunmen To Kill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the dozens of passengers who began their second week as captives inside a sweltering jetliner, Flight 422 has become a journey of terror with mounting physical and psychological tensions. The blue-and-white <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 was hijacked over <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> on a flight from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> eight days ago, but some of the hostages have lost track of time. `` It's been 10 days,'' complained passenger <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Gabandi </PERSON>, who was put on the radio Tuesday by the hijackers to beg for the release 17 pro-Iranian bombers imprisoned in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, the terrorists' main demand. `` This is what we're all waiting for,'' he said plaintively. `` We all want to go home.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> landed at <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION> Friday after a harrowing flight from <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION> in northeast <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The veteran Iraqi pilot, Capt. <PERSON> Youssef </PERSON> <PERSON> Subhi </PERSON>, 53, frantically radioed he was running out of fuel after he was refused permission to touch down at <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>. Since then, the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> hijackers, armed with guns and grenades, have repeatedly demanded that the jumbo jet be refueled. Two captives, their hands tied behind their backs, have been shot in the head and their bodies pushed out of the jet onto the tarmac of the beachside runway. `` The hostages inside the jet must be terrified, wondering who will be next,'' said a Cypriot air traffic controller, one of a team assigned to maintain contact with the hijackers. He asked that his name not be used. `` Every time the hijackers set a new deadline, each passenger must fear that maybe he'll be the one the hijackers pick on when it's not met.'' Passenger <PERSON> Fadel </PERSON> <PERSON> Khaled </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON>, a businessman and cousin of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s emir, <PERSON> Shieik </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON>, could barely talk when the hijackers put him on the radio to plead for fuel. `` We depend on God for our fate,'' he said in a strained voice after reciting a verse from the Koran, Islam's holy book. When he suddenly broke off, the tower asked what was wrong. One of the hijackers snapped back in broken English: `` He is sick. He can not hold his food. He is vomiting.'' The hijackers have reported that several other captives were ailing, but given no details. Two nights ago, one gunman requested Maalox Suspension, an antacid medicine, painstakingly spelling out the name so the tower got it right. He did not say who it was for. One of the four negotiators, who was allowed to step inside the plane once, said he briefly spoke to <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Ebtesam </PERSON>, who with another sister, Anware, are the only women aboard. <PERSON> Ebtesam </PERSON> had blood smeared under her nose. Asked how it got there, the woman said: `` I had a nosebleed. It's because I'm nervous and the air is so dry in here. The 42-year-old flight engineer, <PERSON> Ayed </PERSON> <PERSON> Eid </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamlan </PERSON>, who was hijacked once before in 1984, reported the sky pirates have beaten some of the passengers. Doctors at <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION> morgue reported that both men who were killed had been badly beaten before they were shot by the hijackers, who have threatened to continue a `` slow and quiet massacre'' of their captives. `` The conditions inside the plane must be harrowing by now,'' said the controller, a veteran of several hijacks on this east <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island that because of its location, only 100 miles from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, has become a crossroads for terrorists in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` During the day it must be like a Turkish bath.'' The hijackers repeatedly demanded mobile generators to power the air conditioning system and reported Tuesday that the temperature inside the main cabin soared to 104 degrees Fahrenheit when a generator ran out of fuel. `` Hurry up! Hurry up!'' one hijacker snapped to the tower as he waited for a new generator to be rolled up. `` Is is hot in there?'' the tower asked. `` Yes it is,'' the hijacker snarled. `` It's only 30 degrees -LRB- 86 Fahrenheit -RRB- outside.'' The controller noted: `` That's the first time I've heard him display any emotion. Usually they're calm, very matter-of-fact, even when they've just killed a hostage. `` They rarely raise their voices. They seem well-educated and at least one is well-versed technically. They're the coolest customers I've encountered.'' The window shades are drawn 24 hours a day. The hijackers open the doors to haul up plastic bags of food and refreshments when the delivery teams move away. The passengers and flight crew, along with their captors, have eaten little since Friday. They got a hot meal of meat and vegetables Friday night, but since then have had daily deliveries of bread, cakes, cheese, soft drinks and mineral water. Much of the radio chatter is about technical matters or housekeeping _ such as requests to empty the toilets _ that seem trivial as the deadly drama unfolds. But the threat of violence is never far away, despite the air of normality outside as other jets arrive filled with tourists for the beaches across the bay. When a camouflaged C-130 military transport landed Tuesday, one of the hijackers who was fearful it contained troops to storm the jet yelled into the radio: `` We see a military plane! Identify it!'' The controller explained it was a <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> air force plane on a routine weekly flight supplying Greek officers with the <ORGANIZATION> Cyprus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, and `` nothing to worry about.'' The hijacker said: `` My men were about to shoot at it.''
