</PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>, the chief prosecutor in the case, however, argued that <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> was incorrect. `` Mr. <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> can shout from now to the cows come home ... but it is not going to make the sun come up in the west,'' said <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Melton </PERSON> allowed <PERSON> Antippas </PERSON> to testify, but limited hearsay testimony. <PERSON> Antippas </PERSON> testified he met with <LOCATION> Bahamian </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Lynden </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pindling </PERSON> in 1981 to discuss written complaints he had received from Americans living on <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s Cay. `` I raised this with the prime minister and he said he knew of no such complaints and problems on the island. He asked me who these people were and I declined to tell him,'' said <PERSON> Antippas </PERSON>. He said he also complained to <PERSON> Clement </PERSON> <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON>, home affairs minister in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, and asked that police be stationed on the island to protect Americans and their property. <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> agreed. In January 1982, <PERSON> Antippas </PERSON> said, he went to the island and found that police there had no vehicles and were apparently doing nothing. He returned in April 1983 and found the island nearly deserted. He also collected telephone toll records and ledgers from the island and placed them in the embassy vault in <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION>. In December 1982, a new ambassador was appointed for the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobriansky </PERSON>, and six months later, <PERSON> Antippas </PERSON> said, the governor told him to find another job. The items he had stored in the vault could n't be found, he said. <PERSON> Gorman </PERSON> <PERSON> Bannister </PERS