<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> used give-and-take over the family dinner table to prod his children to excel and he read a Bible story to them nightly, his daughter <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON> recalls as the 20th anniversary of <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s murder nears. Now 36 and practicing environmental law, Mrs. <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON> said in an interview in the current <PERSON> McCall </PERSON>'s magazine that she preferred not to talk about <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s death on June 6, 1968, while running for the Democratic nomination for president. `` I want to remember the happy times, the vibrancy of his presence,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON>, who lives in the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Ruxton </LOCATION> with her literature-professor husband, <PERSON> David </PERSON>, and three daughters. She said her father's arrival home always touched off tickling and roughhousing and later everybody in the big family, except for the very youngest, had dinner together. `` Those mealtimes were school away from school, but we loved them,'' she said. `` My father would toss questions at us about history. ... If we knew the answers we'd yell them out as though we were winning a big jackpot in a quiz show. And if we drew blanks, my father would say quietly, ` You can do better than that.' That made us want to do better.'' She remembered his telling the children, `` Take the hard course, not the easy way. Make the tough decisions.'' She said that around 8:30 p.m. all the children left their bedrooms at <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION>'s call and sat on the floor at the top of the stairs. `` Before the cross that hung there, my father would read Bible stories, one each night, from a children's version of the Old Testament. And we'd sit in total silence, which was unusual for us, entranced. ... `` I never forgot those evenings. Now we read the same Bible stories every night to our children, who are just as enchanted by them as we were.''
