ect last year require Soviet authorities to tell applicants for emigration why their request has been rejected. Jewish activists, however, say the rules are ignored or that overly general reasons are given that do n't tell applicants for an exit visa exactly why their request has been refused. Ms. <PERSON> Gulko </PERSON> formerly was employed as an engineer specializing in ventilation and air conditioning systems. She said she has never been given a specific reason for why she has been unable to get an exit visa. She also said she never engaged in secret work for the government, which Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> has said is the sole legitimate reason that can cause rejection of an application to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Last year, as relations between the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the West improved, more than 8,000 Soviet Jews were permitted to emigrate, nearly eight times as many as the year before and the highest total since 1981. Among those who have left in recent months are longtime Jewish activists and refuseniks <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Begun </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Slepak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ida </PERSON> <PERSON> Nudel </PERSON>. Jewish activists say thousands, if not tens of thousands, of Jews want to emigrate but have been turned down.
