<HEAD>Catty Uproar Over Rare Rodent and Bird</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN RAFAEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City planners thought they had the perfect solution when a developer sought to build homes next to a marsh where endangered species of mice and birds live: Ban all cats from the homes. But that was before the cat lovers began phoning, and one city council member says he'll bring up the issue at next Monday's council meeting `` It's unconstitutional,'' said City Councilman <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Frugoli </PERSON>. `` We'll be the laughingstock of everybody.'' `` It's ridiculous that the city's trying to restrict people from having animals ...,'' he said. `` How do we enforce it? Are we going to have police officers out there checking to see if they have cats?'' But it's not so ridiculous, countered City Planning Director <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, who said the city imposed the ban at the suggestion of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The homes are to be built near swampy grasslands by <LOCATION> Gallinas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> in this suburb about 20 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The swampland is home to the salt marsh harvest mouse and the clapper rail bird, both of which are on state and federal endangered species lists. Permits for the 224-home development were issued March 29 after the city <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> approved construction on condition that felines be banned. `` There's definitely a logic to this,'' Ms. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. `` This is the mouse that has stopped development all over <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> when it is found in an area where development is proposed.'' <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Royce </PERSON>, chief of subdivisions in the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said the cat ban could be the first in the nation to affect private homes. `` I do n't know of a similar proposal,'' he said. The developer, Southwest Diversified, had no problems with the ban. It's a `` reasonable compromise'' between the environment and the need for housing, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Garlinghouse </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diversified </ORGANIZATION>. `` Twenty years ago we would have simply gone in and bulldozed.'' The executive said he has agreed that a section of land that lies between the housing project and the marsh will remain wild, as sort of a buffer zone. Ms. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, who acknowledges getting some irate phone calls from cat lovers, praised the developer for `` being very sensitive to the environmental situation. It was not an issue with the developer. They said ` fine.''' <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Kobetich </PERSON>, field supervisor of the federal wildlife service's <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> endangered species office, said that cats `` are one of our major concerns. They're predators.'' Negotiations aimed at saving the endangered mouse are going on over several planned developments on the east and south sides of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Kobetich </PERSON>. `` We generally arrive at a reasonable solution,'' he said.
