<HEAD>BLM Considering Halting Large-Scale Giveaways of Wild Horses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it is going to decide whether recent allegations of cruelty to animals should mean an end to its practice of giving away large numbers of wild horses. `` We're putting the large-scale adoptions under an intensive review,'' <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> said. But he declined to confirm a report that the no-fee, large-herd `` adoption'' program had been suspended. Since the mid-1970s, the bureau has offered for `` adoption'' the wild horses taken in its roundups from the Western range on payment of $ 125. Use of the term `` adoption'' is really a marketing tool, since after a year the bureau gives the `` foster parent'' title to the horse. Since 1984 the bureau has waived the fee for people willing to take 100 animals or more. <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> said the review was prompted by recent allegations of abuse, including one at <LOCATION> Sheyenne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, where earlier this month bureau officials reclaimed what was left of a herd of 400 horses on a ranch there. Forty-two horses were missing and 87 had died, mostly of dehydration or starvation. The Grand Forks -LRB- <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> last week quoted <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyles </PERSON>, head of the bureau's wild horse and burro division, as saying, `` We're not approving any more than those already approved. Both <PERSON> Boyles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Burford </PERSON>, director of the bureau, were traveling Tuesday and unavailable for comment. <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> would say only, `` The instruction memo has not been issued. Large-scale adoptions are still in our regs.'' <PERSON> Locke </PERSON> said <PERSON> Burford </PERSON> would take up the question when he returns. Last year the bureau transferred 8,600 horses to private caretakers in large-herd, no-fee adoptions. These are generally horses that no one has taken in individual adoptions, and frequently undesirable because older horses are more difficult to break. About 5,000 horses a year are adopted by individuals. The bureau has to round up horses to keep them from eating so much forage that cattle can not graze on the range. It previously killed the surplus animals, but it abandoned that practice in 1982 following protests by animal rights groups.
