<TEXT>
 Presidential press secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday to expand home health care and other services vital to head injury victims, describing vividly their own plight since <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> was shot. `` My name is <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. I am a seven-year survivor of a traumatic brain injury,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said evenly as a hush fell over the packed <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing room. `` I know only too well the tragedy surrounding a head injury. I am pleased that you are taking a keen look at our problems.'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> was shot during the 1981 assassination attempt on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and at one point was reported dead. He delivered his brief statement to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on the handicapped from a wheelchair, with little expression in his face or voice. Though clearly not fully recovered, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> demonstrated during his wife's testimony that his famous sense of humor survives in some form. `` Speaking as a family member, I can tell you that going through that initial trauma is surely difficult, but somehow you do,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. `` It was difficult for me, too,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> interjected dryly, winning a roar of laughter from the audience, which included many head trauma victims. Mrs. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> had received first-rate care, even down to a 24-hour <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> guard by his hospital room door. `` That was so I could n't sneak out,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> interrupted. The rude shock came when <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> was released from the hospital and there was no support network, his wife said. She said she felt trepidation about facing the situation alone and had no one with whom to discuss the best way to handle <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s rehabilitation. Under questioning, Mrs. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said her family's No. 1 need is for home care for her husband, who can not be left alone during a short shopping trip much less the many hours of a full-time workday. `` Jim for example is not able to get out of a chair by himself, and would not be able to leave our home in the event of a fire,'' she said. `` It's very frustrating to see that home health care is not always covered'' by government or private insurance. Mrs. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said families and survivors also need support and counseling programs to cope with the tragedy that has shattered so many lives _ children, parents, spouses and the victims themselves. She said the shooting has had a devastating impact on <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s elderly mother and his 9-year-old son As for <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> himself, she said, `` He laughs and keeps a sense of humor up, but I know that he thinks daily of what he could have been doing.''
