<HEAD>Stocks Rally to Highest Point Since Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices rose again Tuesday as a late splurge of buying pushed the market to its highest point since the October crash. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 14.09 points to close at 2,110.08, its first close above that level since the market collapsed on Oct. 19. The gain was the sixth consecutive rise for a total rise of nearly 130 points. Early in the session stock prices were mixed and the market appeared to lack direction. But computer-guided `` program trading'' late in the day set off a surge of stock buying that pushed up the market. Such programs seek to profit from price disparities between stock index futures and the stocks mirrored by the indexes. Trading volume remained light, which accentuated the move upward once buyers did step in, analysts noted. Analysts said many investors were sitting on the sidelines awaiting fresh economic data, such as the government's report on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for February, which is due Thursday. `` A lot of people are going to play it close to the vest until they see some direction from the numbers coming out,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Vandenberg </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.
