 Satanic and ritualistic practices and beliefs may be a motivating factor in a one form of child abuse, a children's welfare group said Tuesday. `` People have now moved to a new level of how to assault children,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Saxton </PERSON> of Childhelp <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>. `` Just abusing the child in the home is not enough. We've gotten into this very sadistic kind of stuff with children.'' <PERSON> Saxton </PERSON>, who is director of a Childhelp hotline, based his remarks on initial findings of a national study to determine the extent of cult involvement in specific abuse cases. The results represent 36 separate cases, documented by 59 questionnaires from 16 states. He said 97 percent of children reported male and female abusers, 50 percent described six or more perpetrators, and more than 30 percent told of more than 11 persons involved. Sixty percent of the children responding to the questionnaires indicated the incidents lasted from seven months to two years. Seventy-eight percent of the children said they were photographed in the nude, while more than 60 percent said they were photographed during sexual activity. In two-thirds of cases, <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON> said the children said they were drugged, saw or participated in rituals, animal killings and mutilations as part of the incident. About half said they were taken to cemeteries and curches for these rituals. Roughly 46 percent of the children were forced to eat or drink bodily waste, while a little more than 40 percent were forced to ingest what they were told was human flesh or blood. Although <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON> said it would be premature to say the figures represent a national trend, he is receiving calls from therapists nationwide about adult patients exhibiting behavior or experienceing dreams similar to those of some sexually abused children. <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON> told of an incident in which a therapist had a patient who remembered having a baby when she was 13, but could not remember what happened to the child. `` Two days later I get a call from this therapist saying, ` Good God, this woman remembers having to kill her child,''' he said. <PERSON> Sexton </PERSON> also mentioned that one of his adult patients, who had been a sexual abuse victim from ages 12 through 16, gave birth to five children, all of whom `` disappeared'' in the same manner. Childhelp <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> is California-based, non-profit organization that assists child abuse victims and their families through public education, clinical programs, research and its 24-hour child abuse hotline. According to the information from hotline's 148,452 calls last year, the incidence of sexual and physical child abuse is more than double that of the nationally accepted figures. National statistics indicate 11 percent of abuse reports are sexual, while 36 percent of the hotline calls were for sexual abuse. Similarily, national figures indicate 15.5 percent of reported abuse is physical, but calls for physical abuse totaled 37 percent of the hotline calls last year. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverston </PERSON>, Childhelp research director, said many children are being exposed to the threat of AIDS as a result of sexual abuse. The organization and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, were asking the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> to fund a three-year study of those children who are in the high-risk category.
