<HEAD>Soviet Delegation Arrives For Inspection Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A delegation of Soviets arrived in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Tuesday for a second round of talks about on-site monitoring to verify an arms control pact signed at the summit last December, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spokesman said. The dozen or so Soviets arrived at Dulles International Airport on an <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and were to open talks Wedneday with an American team headed by Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON>, said the spokesman, Cmdr. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>. The Soviet team is headed by Gen. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, who helped negotiate the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty under which the superpowers are to destroy nuclear-tipped missiles with ranges from 300 to 3,000 miles. <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON> heads the <ORGANIZATION> On-Site </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, created shortly after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> signed the INF accord at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit last December. In talks scheduled to last until Saturday, <PERSON> Lajoie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> will discuss what a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official called `` housekeeping details,'' such as living quarters for the inspectors, the transportation of equipment, and call signs that aircraft carrying the teams will use while in the other's airspace, said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agency will select and train an estimated 125 people to monitor the destruction of the Soviet missiles and verify that no more are deployed. Thirty days after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> notify each other that the treaty has been ratified and is in effect, members of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> teams will visit 126 sites in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, six in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and one in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> over two months to verify data supplied by the Soviets concerning their forces. The Soviets will visit 21 sites in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> where the missiles have been made or deployed. Once those inspections are complete, teams of 30 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors will be stationed for three months at a stretch over the next 13 years in the small city of <LOCATION> Votkinsk </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, where the Soviets produce a longer range missile that resembles the SS-20, one of the weapons banned under the INF pact. The Soviets will station similar teams in <LOCATION> Magna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, where the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been producing components of <ORGANIZATION> Pershing </ORGANIZATION> 2 missiles, also to be eliminated under the treaty.
