<HEAD>HUD Plans More Housing Vouchers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with testimony before Senate subcommittee</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal housing officials plan to significantly increase the number of people getting vouchers to help pay their rent, Housing and Urban Development Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said Tuesday. The voucher program, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's alternative to building more public housing, now assists about 100,000 low-income families, with another 34,000 to be added by the fall, <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> plans to add another 100,000 families in 1989, he said. Rather than subsidizing housing units, the program gives poor families a voucher which can be used to pay a portion of the rent on living space they choose for themselves. The value of the voucher is fixed according to each family's income, leaving the amount of additional rent flexible. The program was made permanent by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year. `` Vouchers give families the dignity of choice, offering them the opportunity to locate near family and friends, schools, churches and jobs,'' rather than in public housing projects, said <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. He appeared before the subcommittee on HUD-independent agencies to discuss his $ 21.6 billion budget request for fiscal 1989. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 budget is $ 18.6 billion. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said the number of households to be assisted by various <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> programs would increase from 4.3 million in 1988 to 4.4 million next year. Subcommittee Chairman Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boland </PERSON>, D-Mass., questioned <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s conclusion that the major problem for low-income families is not the availability of houses but their affordability <PERSON> Boland </PERSON> said some studies show a severe shortage of low-income housing as units built in the 1960s are converted into more profitable uses. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> quoted <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> statistics putting rental vacancy rates at their highest in 20 years, with an 8.4 percent vacancy rate among apartments renting between $ 200 and $ 249 a month. <PERSON> Boland </PERSON> also questioned <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s estimate last week that it would take between $ 7.5 billion and $ 9.2 billion to bring the nation's 1.3 million public housing units up to modern safety and sanitation standards He said other estimates put the cost as high as $ 20 billion. Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, asked <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> if he is concerned that many middle-income people are being priced out of the housing market. `` I'm not as disturbed as you, because I do n't see that it is such a big problem,'' the secretary said. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, who is the only Cabinet member still in office from among President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s original appointees, noted record sales and record housing starts in recent years. `` Somebody's buying the homes,'' he said. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>, assistant secretary for housing, told the subcommittee several factors have affected middle-class families' ability to buy homes, including a decline in savings brought about partly by increased education costs Meanwhile, former developer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rouse </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should appropriate another $ 3.4 billion a year to support a federal program to increase the supply of low-income and rental housing by the year 2000. <PERSON> Rouse </PERSON>, who chaired an ad hoc committee which studied housing needs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> banking subcommittee that the nation faces the worst housing crisis in the past 10 years. <PERSON> Rouse </PERSON>, who headed his own development company and now is chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, said the $ 3.4 billion would be added to the $ 13.6 billion currently available. Half of the $ 3.4 billion would be allocated to the states, which would be required to match the funds by various means: providing land or distributing money to local authorities. The other half would go directly to cities which would have wide discretion for use of the funds but would not be required to match the money.
