<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A hijacked jet left <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> on Wednesday carrying more than 30 hostages held for over a week by Moslem gunmen demanding freedom for terrorists jailed in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The blue-and-white <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 took off at 1:17 a.m. Wednesday -LRB- 6:17 p.m. EDT Tuesday -RRB- after the hijackers freed 12 hostages. Forty people were believed on board the aircraft after the latest release, including a half-dozen hijackers. The plane was seized a week ago by gunmen demanding freedom for 17 pro-Iranian terrorists held in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The plane was refueled after repeated demands by the hijackers, who have killed two hostages in <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION>. The freed passengers were driven from the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 at around 10:25 p.m. -LRB- 3:25 p.m. EDT -RRB- then taken to <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> General </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, reporters at the scene and hospital officials said. A hijacker told the tower the released included two Palestinians with Jordanian passports and 10 others who were sick, poor or had numerous children. They said the releases were a `` goodwill'' gesture but added also that the Jordanian nationals were freed as a `` present to the uprising in <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>,'' a reference to four months of anti-Israeli violence in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The plane's engines started shortly after the latest passengers were released, and loud bangs rang out across the tarmac. Officials said the noise was caused by the engines. <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and government negotiators held talks with the hijackers before the latest hostages were being freed. The hijackers said earlier in the day that they had on death shrouds. One hijacker, in a statement radioed to