<HEAD>Publisher Says Free and Paid Newspapers Have Common Rivals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newspapers that sell their issues and those that distribute free have greater rivals than each other, <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Ingersoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. Ingersoll's company is the largest free-circulation publisher in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but publishes other newspapers with paid circulation. He bought 10 regional British papers of both kinds in January. `` In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, there are still paid daily publishers who view free newspapers of any kind as a threatening phenomenon, but we do n't happen to feel that way ourselves,'' he told a <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> conference on the newspaper industry. `` Free circulation and paid do n't have to be pitched in mortal combat. Indeed, both have more serious natural enemies, several of which have yet to show their full strength in the U.K. -LRB- <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> -RRB-.'' He said the real rivals include development of local commercial broadcasting, direct mail and outdoor advertising. <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> said his company publishes free-circulation newspapers wherever it publishes paid papers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Also, he said, `` We publish free-circulation newspapers in markets in which other publishers, paid or free, have defaulted on their obligation to deliver dependable readership to local retail advertisers.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ingersoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> is the first foreign company to invest in the British regional press, where `` the free versus paid wars ... are relatively new,'' the publisher said. It acquired the <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Coventry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> and the regional Sunday publication Sunday Mercury, all paid newspapers, and six free weeklies in the <LOCATION> Midlands </LOCATION> region. The privately held company publishes more than 40 daily papers, including the Trentonian, and more than 200 weeklies. It has annual revenues of $ 700 million and employs 11,000 people. `` It is arguable that the traditional paid daily no longer exists,'' <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> said, adding that papers rely on advertising and not circulation revenue for their profits. He said daily newspaper circulation began deteriorating after World War II because populations became more transient, sprawling suburban markets developed and commerical broadcasting grew. Free papers moved into the gap, <PERSON> Ingersoll </PERSON> said.
