<HEAD>Army Commander Killed; Crash Victims Buried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem guerrillas killed the vice commander of the Afghan army's central corps in an attack in the western province of <LOCATION> Parwan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, meanwhile, a <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official told a visiting Italian government delegation that the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> will remove 50,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> during a three-month period beginning May 15, a source said. The statement by First Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> appeared to be the first time an official source gave any indication of the size of the Soviet force backing the Afghan government. Official <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Aqa </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> was assaulted by `` extremist opposition elements'' _ a reference to the guerrillas _ in the town of <LOCATION> Pul </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mattak </LOCATION>. He later died of his wounds, it said, without giving a date. He was buried Tuesday along with several victims of a passenger plane shot down by guerrillas on Sunday, said <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>. Defense and <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials attended the funeral in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, it said. Other victims of the crash, in which 29 people were killed, were buried in the northern province of <LOCATION> Faryab </LOCATION>. The Soviet-made plane had been on a domestic flight in northern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The radio said the guerrillas who downed the plane were `` guided by leaders based in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>,'' referring to the seven-party guerrilla group which maintains headquarters in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Under an accord to be signed Thursday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has agreed to remove all of its soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> within nine months of May 15, the first half of them by Aug. 15. The troop figure provided by <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> would make the size of the Soviet force about 100,000 soldiers. Western sources have estimated there are 115,000 Soviet soldiers in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, but the Soviets never have provided a figure. The Italian source attended the meeting but spoke on condition he not be further identified. <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> told the group of eight Italian lawmakers that half of the Soviet force would leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> within three months, and `` he mentioned 50,000 soldiers,'' the source said. <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> did not provide any further details. The Italian delegation that met with <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> was headed by <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Democrat </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaminio </PERSON> <PERSON> Piccoli </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> of the Italian Chamber of Deputies. Soviet soldiers entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 and replaced one pro-Soviet government with another. They remained to help government forces fight anti-Communist insurgents, who have received aid from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
