<HEAD>Athol Fugard's `The Road to Mecca' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the dry, dusty South African outback, an elderly woman creates an outdoor sculpture garden filled with strange and wondrous things _ camels, wise men, owls, pyramids, a <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON>, mermaids, peacocks, even a mosque made of beer bottles. She calls it her `` Mecca,'' and it is the catalyst for `` The Road to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Athol </PERSON> <PERSON> Fugard </PERSON>'s astonishing and affecting new play which opened Tuesday at off-Broadway's Promenade Theater. <PERSON> Fugard </PERSON> is the South African playwright best known for such works as `` Blood Knot'' and `` Master <PERSON> Harold </PERSON>... and the boys.'' They deal with the pervasiveness of apartheid as well as the necessity and inevitability of seeing everything in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in terms of black and white. `` The Road to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>,'' with its three white characters, touches on an apartheid of a different sort. It concerns an adventurous artist named Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, at odds with and cut off from the rigid and unyielding Afrikaners around her. It's her eccentric art work that severs her from society. Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> stands at the center of a battle between <PERSON> Marius </PERSON>, a staid minister, and <PERSON> Elsa </PERSON>, an embittered, frustrated English teacher. <PERSON> Marius </PERSON> feels Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> should move to a retirement home, while the teacher champions the woman's right to remain where she is and create her exotic statues. The fight for control of Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>'s life and artistic spirit takes a while to develop. <PERSON> Fugard </PERSON> does n't rush his story. He examines each member of this trio with sensitivity and care. Act 1 focuses on the two women. Their relationship is the most interesting aspect of the play. The younger woman admires Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>'s independence, her ability to pursue what she wants, regardless of the consequences. The older woman relishes the companionship of the young teacher whose enthusiasm she admires. The minister comes between them in the second act, a powerful explosion of drama that leads to a heartfelt and hopeful conclusion. <PERSON> Fugard </PERSON>'s mastery of language is never more evident than near the end of Act 2 when Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> explains how she came back to life after a loveless marriage ended. <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryceland </PERSON>, who plays Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, is a revelation. The South African-born actress originally was rejected by Actors Equity from performing in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because it felt she was n't an actress of international stature. Her performance confirms how wrong the union was. The actress, dressed in a gray gunnysack of a dress, commands the stage with her ingratiating smile and honey-combed voice. At first, she projects a childlike enthusiasm but the demeanor is deceptive. Gradually, the woman's crisis of faith is revealed, and the iron will behind her infectious laugh comes through. <PERSON> Fugard </PERSON>, who also directed in a careful, deliberate manner, offers a controlled performance as the rigid clergyman. He has a difficult task _ to portray a sympathetic antagonist who is as much a victim as he is a villain. <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> starts on too strong a note as the volatile teacher, and then has nowhere to go. It's an emotional, showy role, but the part demands more shading than the actress gives it. Miss <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>'s Mecca is never actually seen on stage but a glimpse of its glories is offered in designer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Beatty </PERSON>'s approximation of the woman's living room: Her home literally glitters with the artist's handiwork, lighted by <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Parichy </PERSON> The play ends on a reaffirmation of life, a reaffirmation by the aging artist that recognizes the darkness while celebrating the light. With Miss <PERSON> Bryceland </PERSON> as a most entrancing free spirit, `` The Road to Mecca'' soars above every other play in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
