<HEAD>Report Touts TV Development As Trade Boon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The development of high definition TV offers <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry a chance to improve the trade imbalance for consumer electronics products, according to a government report released Tuesday. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agency, estimates the total potential <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of high definition TV equipment at more than $ 150 billion by the year 2010. `` The message of the report is that there is a huge amount of money at stake and the strength of the consumer electronics industry as well,'' said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> NTIA </ORGANIZATION>, in releasing the report on the final day of the four-day <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> annual convention here. Advanced television technology, including high definition TV, was a hot topic at this year's convention, and most of the dozen or so competing systems under development were demonstrated. The technology produces clearer images with more brilliant colors on a wider TV screen. Broadcasters are concerned that a Japanese lead in developing a high definition technology could put them at a competitive disadvantage to cable TV, video cassette recorders and satellite distribution systems if the Japanese system, which is not compatible with existing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television sets, takes hold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON> said he anticipates that HDTV will follow the same path as color television sets and video cassette recorders, though he said he could not predict how fast sales of HDTV equipment will grow. `` That will turn on general economic conditions, prices of equipment and the availability of software,'' he said. The report, however, says that if HDTV sales grow as fast as color receivers and VCRs, the new products would find their way into about 1 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> households by 1997 and grow to 93.9 percent in 2008, when total sales of HDTV equipment would reach $ 144 billion. The potential sales are `` immense,'' the report said, and `` substantial participation by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers'' in this developing market could help restore balance in the trade and federal budget deficits. The debate over HDTV development in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been over deciding on an industry transmission standard. <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON> said he believes a standard can be agreed upon by 1991.
