<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> train No. 392 left <LOCATION> Carbondale </LOCATION> at mid-afternoon as usual, but when it pulled into <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s Union Station about seven hours later, five people were dead after two collisions with the locomotive, authorities said Tuesday. A young Southern Illinois couple and two of their children died Monday when their car turned off a parallel road near <LOCATION> Effingham </LOCATION> and crossed the track in front of the train about 90 minutes into its run, police and <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> officials said. About 3 -LCB- hours later, a 20-year-old woman was killed when her car skirted horizontal crossing gates and struck the train near <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION>, about 60 miles south of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, officials said. `` You do n't forget things like this. ... You get the shakes,'' said engineer T.B. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who was operating the train when the second crash occurred. None of the train's more than 50 passengers was injured, said <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Marciniak </PERSON>. She said the two train drivers were not responsible for the deaths. `` They were powerless to avoid the accidents, and no disciplinary action is planned,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Marciniak </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> had contacted <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> operations personnel Tuesday about the accidents. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Loftus </PERSON>, a spokesman for the agency in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said he was unaware of any investigation but that his agency might have called to make sure no federal railroad laws had been violated. The victims of the first accident were identified as <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, 26, of <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Clede </PERSON>; his wife, <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON>, 25; their 4-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, and 3-year-old son, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>, said state Police Sgt. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Boldrey </PERSON>. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said fireman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, 55, was driving when the run began. They both saw the Chandler car turn off a parallel road and head slowly toward the track. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said he did not believe the family saw the train at the crossing, marked with a crossing symbol but no gate or lights. `` I could see the female occupant of the car, and she never looked at us. ... I thought I saw the woman holding a child. `` Mr. <PERSON> White </PERSON> had already applied the brakes,'' <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said. `` He started blowing the whistle. Then we put the brakes in emergency, but it was too late.'' He said the engine had been traveling about 76 mph and came to a halt one-third of a mile down the track. Ms. <PERSON> Marciniak </PERSON> said she did not know what the authorized speed limit was in that area but said the train was traveling within it. `` There was nothing the guy could have done to stop it,'' Ms. <PERSON> Marciniak </PERSON> said of the train's driver. She said the car exploded on impact. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, an unemployed saw-mill worker, and his wife had three other children, said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Pagel </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Pagel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funeral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Edgewood </LOCATION>. The train was delayed about an hour and then headed north again, with <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> taking the controls about halfway through the 300 mile run _ a routine switch. The train passed through <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION> after dark at the maximum 79 mph when the railway men saw a car approach rapidly from the west, <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said. `` The crossing signals were working, the gates were down, and we were blowing the whistle,'' he said. But the car moved into the left lane as if to bypass the gates, <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said. The vehicle struck the train's front wheels, causing what he described as `` a minor jolt'' that destroyed the compact car. <PERSON> Annette </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanshew </PERSON>, who lived outside <PERSON> Bourbonnais </PERSON>, died in the crash, said Deputy <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Coroner <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gessner </PERSON>. Last year, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> ranked second in the nation with 481 accidents at rail crossings, Ms. <PERSON> Marciniak </PERSON> said, behind <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> with 625.
