<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge refused Tuesday to overrule a ban ordered by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> last month on the use of padded shoes on Tennessee Walking Horses. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> denied breeders and displayers of the high-gait show horses a temporary restraining order to lay aside Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s order prohibiting the use of the 4-inch-thick pads on the horses' front hooves. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> issued the order on March 25 after <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> had ruled four days earlier that the department's present regulations allowing use of the pads to accent the breed's high gait violated the 1970 Horse Protection Act. The 1970 law was intended to eliminate the practice of `` soring'' _ using chemicals or devices to accent a horse's gait through the infliction of pain to the animal _ in the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walker </LOCATION> industry. Whether the 4-inch pads, sometimes called stacks, `` sore'' or cause pain to a horse has been a legal dispute in <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON>'s court for the past four years through a suit by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> described the pads, which effectively elevate the front of a horse and thus shift its weight to its rear legs, as being similar to high-heeled shoes that a women might decide to quit wearing because they hurt her feet. `` The horses, however, do n't seem to have a choice,'' he added. The <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Breeder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and a new group called Friends of the Show Horse formed in response to <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s ruling had petitioned <PERSON> Gasch </PERSON> for the restraining order <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, an attorney for the latter group, argued that <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> had overstepped the judge's March 25 ruling by immediately implementing the ban instead of going through the normal, lengthy process of rewriting the regulations after first holding hearings and seeking comments. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which had defended its present regulations and agreed with the breeders that the pads were legal, has started that process of redrafting them. But in the interim, it is prohibiting the padded shoes. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s action caused the immediate cancellation of 11 <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horse </ORGANIZATION> shows and threatens another 24 scheduled between now and the end of April around the country. `` It's like <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Shelbyville </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, D-Tenn., whose district includes the town that is site to the annual Tennessee Walking Horse National Celebration, the industry's largest <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> estimated that the show held each year just prior to Labor Day pumps about $ 35 million into the <LOCATION> Shelbyville </LOCATION> area's economy `` It's the flashy, fast-gaited horses that draw the crowds,'' he said. `` People in the business tell me the horses without pads are not as exciting,'' However, <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, who owns a small stable of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Walkers in <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said she is now showing five horses that have never had pads put on their hooves. `` They do n't need to use them,'' she said of the devices. `` It just makes it easier and quicker to train them. And for people running large farms, that means they can just run that many more horses through.''
