<HEAD>Dining Club Thrives on Civilized Pleasures of the Table</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The lighting is soft, the food and wine exquisite, the conversation witty and sophisticated _ ingredients for a perfect evening. But the men and women at the elegant restaurant are more interested in salmon mousse than sizzling amour. <PERSON> Dalliance </PERSON>, though welcome, is not the goal of The Single Gourmet _ a less romantic but frequently more satisfying pleasure lies behind the organization with about 10,000 members in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` It's probably the best way to meet people,'' said <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>, who began the club in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1982. `` It's not a dating agency. It's not a matrimonial agency. It's a dining club. We try to bring people together for good food and congenial conversation.'' The organization's recipe, stirred by changes in courtship and fascination with the arts of the kitchen, has been successful. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> branch has grown to 2,600 members, and 14 independent chapters have opened in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Members pay up to $ 75 a year to join The Single Gourmet and $ 25-50, not including wine, for meals at restaurants or on other outings. Most are upper-middle-class professionals _ lawyers, business executives, stockbrokers and doctors, <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. In keeping with the classy, low-key approach, members are not afflicted with name tags, but are identified discreetly at tables of six to 10 with placecards bearing only first names. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, about 35 members of The Single Gourmet recently enjoyed salmon tortellini, pear and parsnip soup, lamb with couscous and other specialities of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> cuisine at Cafe Majestic, a popular restaurant in a restored Victorian hotel. `` I've wanted to come to this restaurant ever since it opened, but I never dared come by myself,'' said <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON>, 49, a medical secretary. `` So this is a real option for me.'' The chapter, about 18 months old, has about 270 members in the <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area. One member travels from <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> to attend its dinners, winery tours and other functions, which occur about twice a month. Some regulars simply find The Single Gourmet a way to fit a social life into their busy schedules. `` It forces you to go out. For instance, I would not on a Tuesday night go out to Cafe Majestic or someplace like it,'' said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sclafani </PERSON>, a designer in his 30s. `` It gives you a nice experience trying different restaurants and lets you experiment without, as a single man, having to go out on a date,'' he said. Others, like <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sternitzke </PERSON>, first used the club as a way to learn about good restaurants and find friends in a new city. He was hooked when he ended up belly dancing at a <LOCATION> Moroccan </LOCATION> restaurant at the first Single Gourmet dinner he attended a year and a half ago. <PERSON> Sternitzke </PERSON>, 35, credits the club for introducing him _ a native of the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> raised on `` meat-and-potatoes stuff'' _ to culinary adventure. `` I've tasted food I ca n't even say,'' he said. `` And I've tried food when I've asked them not to tell me what it is until I've eaten it. But all the diners agreed they had n't joined The Single Gourmet as a singles club or dating service. `` I just enjoy meeting people. If it was single and married people, I'd probably join then, too,'' said <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>, who began attending dinners six months ago. <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON>, who declined to give her last name, said sex was n't a factor in the civilized pleasure of enjoying food with others. `` When you're eating lovely food, you want to look across the table and say, ` This is wonderful; you must have a taste,''' she said. `` I do n't care if it's with men or women.'' But changing sexual behavior has definitely helped The Single Gourmet, members and coordinators said. `` It just seemed like an idea that came at the right time,'' <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. `` It was the time -LRB- the novel and movie -RRB- ` Looking for Mr. <PERSON> Goodbar </PERSON>' was giving singles bars and discos a bad name. ... You almost had to make up your mind about someone on eye contact. That's hardly the way to get to know somebody.'' But while people may not be looking for love when they join, sometimes they find it anyway. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> chapter has seen 28 marriages of club members in six years, <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>, a retired film importer, owns The Single Gourmet name and sells licenses for branches, which operate independently although members may attend dinners and other Single Gourmet events in other cities. End Adv for Wed PMs, April 20
