<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Israel _ 40th Birthday in a Time of Trouble</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The main story of four.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> turns 40 this week, beset by a rebellion among Palestinians who have spent more than half that time under occupation and a wrenching debate on the young nation's future. The Arab uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> has drained much of the joy from a year-long birthday celebration that climaxes April 22, which coincides on the the Hebrew calendar this year with May 14, 1948, the date <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was founded. A poetry festival and a $ 10 million rock music extravaganza in the <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> are going ahead but plans to bring singer Barbra Streisand, tennis star <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Evert </PERSON> and the rock group <PERSON> Pink </PERSON> <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> collapsed. Officials had hoped to demonstrate <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s achievements and acceptance during the anniversary year. Instead, canceled plans and the absence of foreign heads of state underline its vulnerability. Much of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s success has been in developing military power, the result of five wars with neighboring Arab states. For example, it ranks sixth in the world in arms exports, which bring in about $ 1 billion a year. There also is a flourishing cultural life, especially in a range of music from Hebrew punk-rock to that great national cultural achievement, the Israeli Philharmonic. Since Dec. 8, when the violence began, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has been consumed by the question of what to do with the territories captured from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. For the first time the issue is likely to be the focus of elections, now scheduled for November. Liberal politicians say 20 years of occupation has had a corrosive effect on morality and does not square with being a `` light unto nations'' the goal declared by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s first prime minister, the late <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Gurion </PERSON>. <PERSON> Abba </PERSON> <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>, elder statesman of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said growth of character has not matched the country's growth in material wealth and military power. `` We anticipated that within a period of 40 years we would have outlived the rhetoric of struggle and resistance and would be moving into some kind of drama and romance in social creativity,'' the former foreign minister said. `` Modern <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> does not owe the same allegiance, debt or devotion to its traditional Jewish character, and it very rarely compares its actions to criteria that come from the Jewish ethical tradition.'' He said democracy was being undermined by the emergency measures of occupation, and the cooperative spirit of pioneer days was being supplanted by materialism. Such misgivings are not shared by the rising star of the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc, <PERSON> Benyamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Netanyahu </PERSON>, who recently resigned as ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. He said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s success `` borders on the miraculous.'' Half a century ago, <PERSON> Netanyahu </PERSON> said, the Jewish people had crawled from the Holocaust and the possibility of building a national life seemed hopelessly remote. `` Yet in a few years the Jews recovered their homeland, fought off armies that assaulted them, liberated their ancient capital, built a modern economy, theaters, universities and concert halls, and revived an ancient tongue,'' he declared. <PERSON> Netanyahu </PERSON>, whose brother <PERSON> Yonathan </PERSON> was killed leading the daring 1976 rescue of hijacked airline hostages at <LOCATION> Entebbe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>, said the Arab threat is undiminished. `` The grim truth remains that the majority of the Arab world still refuses to accept <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist, and still seeks to wage war against it, war by different means, including the present means of mass violence and media stampede,'' <PERSON> Netanyahu </PERSON> said. In the former ambassador's view, withdrawal from the occupied lands would shrink <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s waist to a 10-mile-wide strip against the sea, with thousands of young Palestinians holding rockets instead of stones. The left believes <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is strong and secure enough to risk trading land for peace and that greater danger lies in keeping the occupied territories and trying to rule the hostile and rapidly growing popuatlion of 1.5 million Arabs. Palestinian intellectuals attribute the sudden explosion of anger and violence Dec. 8 to three factors: _ The <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> question was ignored by the U.S.-Soviet summit last December and given secondary priority to the Iran-Iraq war at the Arab summit in November _ Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> expressed satisfaction with the status quo and a desire to make the occupied land a permanent part of `` Greater <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ Daily frustrations about army rule radicalized younger Arabs A generation of Palestinians has been born and grown to adulthood since 1967, resentful of occupation and less intimidated by the might of the Israeli military. Many also have been attracted to the Moslem fundamentalism spreading through the Arab world One result of these forces has been a young, underground leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> that has taken charge of the rebellion and is directing it. <PERSON> Saeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Erakat </PERSON>, a political science professor at An <ORGANIZATION> Najah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, said: `` The uprising is a message to the Israelis, the Americans and the Arabs: We do n't want to become Israeli. We are not a minority, but a people, and therefore we demand our right to self-determination,'' Many Israelis say the Arabs fail to comprehend or accept the historical connection Jews feel to the land. <PERSON> Yehuda </PERSON> <PERSON> Avni </PERSON> immigrated from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in 1949 and built the <PERSON> Vered </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagalil </PERSON> ranch near the Sea of <LOCATION> Galilee </LOCATION> with his wife <PERSON> Yona </PERSON>. Across the road from his stable of pure-bred Arabian horses is the ruin of the home of an Israelite who lived about 200 B.C. `` We both picked this site with its beautiful view for our farms,'' said <PERSON> Avni </PERSON>, 60. `` I feel a kind of kinship with him. I feel I am part of a chain. The sense of continuity is something vivid, and it gives depth to my life.'' In <LOCATION> Efrat </LOCATION>, a Jewish settlement eight miles south of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, Rabbi <PERSON> Shlomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Riskin </PERSON> showed a reporter the rocky hills on which he has founded a community of 300, mostly religious Jews. Seeking to dispel the image of settler as fanatic, <PERSON> Riskin </PERSON> stresses his desire for coexistence with Arabs. The difficulty of achieving it is illustrated by his experience with <PERSON> Majid </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> handyman who taught <PERSON> Riskin </PERSON> Arabic. `` I studied with him a few times a week,'' the rabbi said. `` He had gefilte fish at my home on Friday evening a number of times. We had what I thought were very good relations.'' Then one day a bomb was planted just outside <LOCATION> Efrat </LOCATION> and one of the prime suspects was <PERSON> Majid </PERSON>, who disappeared. `` I teach my children and myself to respect every human being as innocent until proven guilty,'' <PERSON> Riskin </PERSON> said. `` At the same time, I have to make sure that I protect myself.'' The <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict touches almost every aspect of life, even the 110-piece <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philharmonic </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ely </PERSON> <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>, 38, a clarinetist and son of <PERSON> Abba </PERSON> <PERSON> Eban </PERSON>, said the unseen impact was brought home to him when he returned from studying in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, the tempo of life was rapid. `` Whenever I would hear myself playing something here, it always seemed a little fast, a little strident, a little more nervous,'' he said. `` When you live here, there is this rhythm that you take on, and it does affect the music making.''
</TEXT>
