<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Israel _ What Caused the Rebellion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a four-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Palestinians say a feeling they have been neglected by the world and other Arabs, tough statements from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and day-by-day frustrations of occupation led to the rebellion in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The spark was a traffic accident Dec. 8 in which an Israeli army truck killed four Arabs near the <LOCATION> Jabaliya </LOCATION> refugee camp in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Tensions were such that <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> saw it not as an accident but as revenge for the stabbing death in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> two days earlier of <PERSON> Shlomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakel </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> businessman. Anger had been building among Palestinians because they felt abandoned by <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nations and the world community. The Arab summit at <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, in November, and the U.S.-Soviet summit in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in December, did not give priority to the Palestinian issue. `` It was clear to us that we had been put on the shelf,'' said <PERSON> Saeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Erakat </PERSON>, a political science professor at An <ORGANIZATION> Najah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. `` The message -LRB- of the uprising -RRB- is that we do n't wish to become Israelis. We are not a mere community or a minority living in greater <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. We are a people ... and we demand our liberty and our right to self-determination.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> rubbed salt in the wound by noting publicly that the Arab summit put the Iran-Iraq war ahead of the Palestinian issue. He and other right-wing leaders suggested the status quo could continue indefinitely and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had a right to keep the lands it captured in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. This deepened the bitterness. Palestinian statements became extreme in rejecting negotiations for a peaceful settlement. An example of the harder line could be found in the poetry of <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Darwish </PERSON>, an Israeli Arab living in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> who had favored Israeli-Palestinian dialogue. Many saw his poem `` Those Who Pass Between Fleeting Words'' as a demand for all of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, not just the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. About the Israelis, it says: `` O those who pass between fleeting words, `` Carry your names, and be gone; `` Rid our time of your hours, and be gone; `` Steal what you will from the blueness of the sea and the sand of memory.'' <PERSON> Sari </PERSON> <PERSON> Nusseibeh </PERSON>, a Palestinian intellectual who advocates a negotiated settlement, said many want all <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> included in a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state just as some Israelis want all the land for the Jewish state. `` The question is whether both sides are ready to settle for less than what they want,'' he said. `` Are they prepared to settle for some kind of partition of this land?'' He said most Palestinians are ready for a two-state solution, but this feeling is `` like a comet that comes close to the earth. If one wants to use it, one has to grab it while it is there.'' He also cited the cumulative affects of 20 years of occupation on the new generation, noting that half the people of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> are under 20 years old and 77 percent under 28. For them, he said, leadership status is `` determined by how many times you have been in jail, how bad was the interrogation and has anybody in your family died fighting. `` The more ` yeses' to such questions the more of a leader you became within your neighborhood or community,'' he added. As Palestinian militancy grew, the deterrent power of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s army was weakened Palestinians saw Shiite Moslem guerrillas drive the Israelis out of south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1985 with a determined guerrilla campaign. Then, in late November 1987, a Palestinian guerrilla sailed over <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s well-defended northern border with a hang glider and killed six soldiers. Israeli analysts said the attack encouraged Palestinians to challenge the army in the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
