<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil prices have leaped to the highest level of the year, partly reflecting speculation that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> would be able to recruit help from outside producers to constrict world supplies. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the May-delivery contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate crude oil jumped $ 1.01 per barrel on Monday to $ 17.89, the highest level since a closing of $ 17.85 reached Jan. 5. It was one of the biggest one-day moves ever, traders said. Some traders and analysts said the gain was not sustainable. But others said it signaled a more fundamental change in market sentiment that indicated the end of a low-price era in the petroleum business.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has indicated the world's top industrial countries are near agreement on a proposal to use the price of gold and other commodities to help in the international coordination of exchange rates. The disclosure Monday came as representatives of the 151-nation <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> began five days of high-level meetings with exchange rates, trade issues and Third World debt dominating the agenda.
