<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The most detailed assessment of the nation's business schools in nearly 30 years has found widespread complacency, poor planning and a lack of contact with the business world But the 372-page report, released Monday at a national convention of business schools, drew immediate fire from deans and corporate officials who said the report did n't go far enough in addressing social and ethical issues, including minority recruitment. The report chided schools for preaching long-term planning in the corporate world, but doing little planning themselves beyond the next semester.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The airline smoking ban that goes into effect April 23 on commercial aircraft will apply to any flight scheduled for two hours or less even if delays cause the flight to take longer, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> says. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> required the smoking ban on short flights in legislation last year. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued its final rules on the prohibition Monday, although the general outline of the new restrictions has been known for months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s planned closing of its <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> auto plant would cost $ 209 million in welfare and unemployment benefits, along with lost taxes, for the first two years after the shutdown, a union-commissioned study says. The analysis released Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> estimated that the plant's closing would cost federal, state and local governments a total of $ 38,000 for each unemployed <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> worker. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> announced in January it plans to end auto production at <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> by Sept. 30, resulting in the layoffs of 5,500 workers.
</TEXT>
