<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The American public may be less willing than the television industry believes to embrace a high-resolution TV system with improved picture quality, clearer images and more brilliant color, according to a new study. The results of the study, released Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, `` contradict the accepted wisdom ... which posits that high definition TV knocks the socks off everyone who sees it.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market edged higher in quiet trading Monday, pushing the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials up 5.80 to 2,095.99, a new post-crash closing high. Bond prices tumbled by as much as $ 10 for every $ 1,000 in face value in response to inflation speculation caused by soaring oil prices. The dollar rose against most major currencies while gold prices were mixed. Copper futures prices fell sharply, livestock and meat futures rose and grains and soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
