<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise; Other Markets Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices have soared to their highest level so far this year, with the runup stirring inflation fears that pushed interest rates sharply higher in the credit markets. Traders said oil prices rose Monday partly on speculation that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> would encourage other oil producers to rein in production. The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' price monitoring committee, which met over the weekend, said it would meet soon with non-OPEC exporters to consider shared production restraints. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the May-delivery contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark crude oil, jumped $ 1.01 per barrel to close at $ 17.89, its highest level this year. Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale heating oil rose 2.42 cents a gallon to 47.88 cents, and wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 2.18 cents a gallon to 50.95 cents. Oil market experts debated whether the gain was sustainable. Some believe the jump in prices may be signaling an end to the recent low-price era in the petroleum business. The sharp run-up had a negative impact on the credit markets, where the yield on the bellwether 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond rose to 8.77 percent from 8.68 percent late Friday. The stock market edged slightly higher, extending last week's rally despite some resistance from sellers The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.80 to 2,095.99 on top of last week's 102.13-point jump to new closing highs since the crash last fall The dollar rose against most major currencies except the Canadian dollar, while gold prices were mixed.
</TEXT>
