<HEAD>T-Bills Mixed In Latest Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities were mixed in the government's latest auction, with rates on three-month bills unchanged and rates on six-month bills edged down slightly. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 6.4 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.98 percent on Monday, the same as last week. Another $ 6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.19 percent, down from 6.21 percent last week. The three-month bill rate this week and last was the highest since these bills averaged 6 percent on Dec. 14. The 6.19 percent rate for six-month bills was the lowest since 6 percent on March 28. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 6.16 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,848.80 and 6.48 percent for six-month bills selling for $ 9,687.10. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, was 7.01 percent last week, up from 6.78 percent the week before.
