<HEAD>Iowa Attorney General Sues Credit Card Giant Over Consumer Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawsuit seeking to force <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> to obey <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> consumer credit laws potentially could affect other companies that, like <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>, offer credit cards in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> but base their card operations elsewhere, the state's attorney general says. Attorney General <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> filed a federal lawsuit Monday seeking to sto <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's biggest credit card issuer, from applying the less stringent credit laws of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, where its credit card operation is based, to other states. The suit contended that although the courts consistently have allowed credit card issuers to use the laws of their home state in setting interest rates wherever they operate, that power should not apply to other consumer credit issues. `` We are challenging the assumption that they can export the laws of states which have few consumer protections into states like <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> that have stronger protections for their citizens,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said at a news conference announcing the suit. `` The suit could affect every bank that has a national credit card operation,'' he said. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said other states had indicated interest in joining the action. <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, S.D. office referred reporters' calls to its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters. Spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McQuire </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said that while the company had not seen the suit, it did comply with federal law. <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> is the banking subsidiary of the New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest bank holding company. It is accused of collecting late charges and other fees that are allowed under <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> law but are banned in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. The company has issued about 15 million credit cards nationwide but insists that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s consumer laws govern its cards wherever they are issued. There are 36,000 <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MasterCard </ORGANIZATION> and Visa cards issued in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said although <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> has deregulated credit card interest rates, it also has banned late payment fees and insufficient funds check charges. <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> also requires companies give three months notice before changing the terms of a credit card contract. `` The banks argue that <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> law does n't apply in this situation,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` We say our -LRB- state -RRB- law does protect Iowans.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> also said the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> law gave <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> a competitive advantage over Iowa-based issuers who had to follow their state's stricter credit rules. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s suit seeks a ban on collection of the late payment fees, plus unspecified civil penalties and a refund of any payments which have been collected. The state targeted <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> for the suit because it is the biggest card issuer, although other companies may be sued as well, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. The state failed to reach an out-of-court settlement over the issue with <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>, he said. The nation's top 10 credit card companies have about 64 million cards outstanding, representing accounts of more than $ 32 billion.
