<HEAD>Japan Notes Shift in Economy as Fiscal-Year Surplus Falls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A change in the structure of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy contributed to the first decline in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s fiscal-year trade surplus in eight years, government and private analysts said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s overall trade surplus dropped 15.3 percent in the fiscal year ended March 31 to $ 76 billion from $ 89.7 billion in the previous fiscal year. It was the first decline since 1979, when <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s oil import bill soared because of the second oil crisis. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> posted its first annual decline since 1982, dropping 2.2 percent to $ 50.9 billion from a record $ 52 billion the year before. `` A shift toward the direction of a decline in trade surplus is taking place at a steady pace,'' said <PERSON> Nobuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Murakami </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s Export Division. The yen's rapid appreciation against the dollar the past two years and the government policy to promote domestic demand were major factors in the decline in the surplus, <PERSON> Murakami </PERSON> said. The yen has roughly doubled in value against the dollar since its most recent low in February 1985. In September 1985, monetary authorities from seven major industrialized countries agreed to drive down the dollar's value to help reduce the huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and less competitive, while imported products are cheaper in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> sent 35.8 percent of its exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in fiscal year 1987, down from 38 percent the previous year. Its exports to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> increased to 16.7 percent from 15.4 percent, and to Southeast Asian countries to 23.7 percent from 20.6 percent. `` It is clear that some major Japanese products, including automobiles, are losing their competiveness on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, though personal computers and other office equipment remain in high demand,'' said <PERSON> Taku </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiramatsu </PERSON>, assistant manager of the <ORGANIZATION> research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hiramatsu </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s auto exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which accounted for about 30 percent of the nation's total exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, `` will be getting further squeezed in the future'' because several Japanese automakers will be making car in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1990s. Japanese automakers have fallen short of the government-set export quota of 2.3 million passenger cars during the year, the first such shortfall since <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> began limting its auto exports to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market in 1981, local news reports said Tuesday. An official of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said the figures for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s car exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be announced late this month, and the volume would be `` far below'' the 2.3 million vehicles sent to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> the previous year. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, blamed the shortfall on the higher yen and the `` slower-than-expected increase in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car market.'' Japanese car makers have raised their export prices to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by more than 20 percent on the average over the past two years to make up for losses stemming from the dollar's depreciation `` More significant results in the reduction of -LRB- <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s -RRB- trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will surely come in years to come,'' <PERSON> Murakami </PERSON> said. `` It's just two years since the yen's appreciation began.''
