<NOTE>For Release Sunday April 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japan's Stock Market Glows As Others Glimmer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Japanese stock market's unrelenting climb to new heights since Black Monday has made the land of the rising sun and its booming economy the envy of every market struggling to regain lost momentum. Unlike the crash, when markets from <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> plummeted in reaction to Wall Street's collapse, the recovery of world markets since Oct. 19 has been relatively uneven. Markets have followed the pace of their own economies, and investors who once roamed the globe in search of equities have returned to the backyard markets they know best. `` I do n't think I could describe any spillover effects,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief economist at <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's more the case that stock markets seem to be tracking economic growth internally. So far this year, major stock markets outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are up about 13.5 percent, according to an index compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market is up about 4.5 percent. European markets have turned in a mixed performance since the crash. The <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> exchange is up on takeover activity; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s market is sluggish; and a slow-growing <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> economy is taking its toll on the Bourse. But if those markets show glimmers of life, the advance has been blinding in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, home of the world's biggest equities market. While the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average has sputtered to and fro beneath pre-crash levels, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s key market barometer has reached stunning all-time highs with ease. The key <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index breezed its way into record territory in early April. `` The story this year really is mostly a story about <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Sladkus </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION>. But, he noted, the market's momentum is n't due to its magnetic attraction for investors outside the island nation. `` It's totally due to domestic considerations,'' <PERSON> Sladkus </PERSON> said. Spurred by a roaring financial boom, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s stock market is reaping the benefits of a surge in corporate profits, a sharp increase in consumption and tax reforms that are likely to prompt consumers to move their money out of savings accounts and into equities. While the quick about-face is n't causing Japanese investors to lose any sleep, some on the other side of the ocean watch with furrowed brows. `` There's concern that with the market going up so strongly and with the economy growing that maybe the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> is not going to be as accommodative,'' <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said, noting that some fear <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s central bank `` could take away one important underpinning of the market _ the liquidity that helped spur the growth'' in the first place. `` Nobody is quite comfortable that a country the size of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and with half the population of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has the biggest stock market, even though -LRB- the Japanese -RRB- seem to do everything right,'' said <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wien </PERSON>, managing director and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index remains about 25 percent below its level just prior to the crash. Despite the fact that the market has been extremely volatile, analysts are n't too concerned about the speed of its recovery. `` The equity market was overvalued before the crash,'' said <PERSON> Randal </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, a market strategist with the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` There's no reason to go right back up to that level yet.'' The market has been supported by an increase in the number of companies buying back their own shares, heightened takeover activity, better-than-expected corporate profits and relief that the economy was n't hit harder by the crash. Thanks to the takeover battle for <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION>, the largest Belgian corporation, the <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> Bourse has put in the best performance among the European exchanges. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, where the stock exchange shut down for four days following Black Monday, trading volume stalled and investor confidence had to be rebuilt from the ground up. But the market is enjoying some spillover enthusiasm from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, since `` the Asian investment community is linked together,'' <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> noted. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, on the other hand, is a `` dog, if you will; it's a real barker,'' <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said. `` They've been experiencing sluggish growth, their monetary policy remains restrictive, and their currency is appreciating, which makes it difficult for German firms to sell their products overseas for a profit,'' he said. Trading volume throughout the world has been relatively light, which analysts say is a sign of confusion among investors. To alleviate fears of the unknown, international investors went home. `` People were operating in markets overseas that they did n't understand that well, and so they brought their money home These markets may not be doing so well, but at least investors understand them,'' <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 17</NOTE>
