picking up 4th graf pvs, ``Airline, Boeing; Boeing newser scheduled
for 2:30 p.m. EDT, no lede planned; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is investigating safety complaints from airlines about <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 and 767 widebody jets and has issued a safety inspection directive for one of the aerospace company's jetliner models. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials revealed Monday that an `` airworthiness directive'' on the 747-200 was issued Friday because of reports that fuel leaking into cargo compartments. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> officials refused Monday to respond to the airline complaints or comment on the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> action, but said they would hold a news conference later. However, <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Condit </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>, was quoted in today's editions of The Wall Street Journal as saying letters from the airlines represent `` communications that go on between us and airlines all the time. That's how we make our products better.'' Airline, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials have noted that none of the defects cited to date has been linked to a crash or other major damage, but the directive warned, `` Fuel in this -LRB- cargo -RRB- compartment could result in a fire and substantial damage.'' The directive said the leaks were caused by loose or broken bolts that attach fuel tanks to the wings and called for repairs `` before further flight.'' <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> officials said the order applied to 317 operating 747-200s. <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Wantiez </PERSON> of the local <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> office said Monday the investigation also would cover airline complaints ranging from wrong parts to incorrectly installed firefighting systems. `` We are putting together a plan this week to deal with these complaints and to determine what actions must be taken to assure compliance with federal regulations,'' <PERSON> Wantiez </PERSON> said. He said the inspection order followed reports of incidents by <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Aerolineas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Argentinas </ORGANIZATION> and a leasing company, starting Nov. 21 with a <ORGANIZATION> JAL </ORGANIZATION> report in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> of a fuel leak involving a bold that had broken from corrosion. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> confirmed Monday that letters citing problems in 767s and 747s had been received from <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Problems cited by <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> included a wing flap disintegrating in flight on the first day of service, smoke from a misassembled power unit that caused an emergency landing, and problems in a fire extinguisher system. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION>'s senior vice president for operations, said his company's maintenance crews found three 767-200s with faulty pipelines that carry firefighting chemicals to the forward and rear cargo compartments. `` The pipes were misrouted,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` If you light them off for the forward belly system they go off in the rear.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said that after being informed by American, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> found one faulty system on its production line and All Nippon and JAL found several in their planes.
