<HEAD>Crash Taints Attraction of Investment Banking For Many MBAs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When recruiters for accounting giant <ORGANIZATION> Touche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> visited graduate business schools earlier this year, students scrambled to get interviews. At the same time, the venerable investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had trouble finding good candidates. The contrast illustrates what students, school officials and campus recruiters agree is a disillusionment with Wall Street careers in the aftermath of the October stock market crash and a corresponding surge of interest in high-paying consulting and accounting professions. `` We found here that the presentations investment banks made were not attended well at all,'' said <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Watts </PERSON>, director of career counseling and placement at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s J.L. <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. `` That's very different than in the last five years, when you could hardly get in the door of a presentation.'' Graduate business students participating in a recent conference at Northwestern said that consulting positions, which offer starting salaries ranging from $ 50,000 to $ 100,000, are a lot more attractive than investment banking careers now because of the employment uncertainty raised by the crash. `` A good part of my class had pegged hopes on Wall Street,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, a 28-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> business student at the conference. `` You see a lot of chameleons out there. Suddenly they're all into consulting.'' Several schools have projected sharp reductions in the number of students who will go into investment banking this year. At <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON>, for example, only about 12 percent will accept Wall Street offers, down from 17 percent last year. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> expects about 15 percent, down from 28 percent, and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> expects about 15 percent, down from 25 percent. Wall Street firms themselves have been curtailing campus recruitment drives this year, partly because they are undergoing their own post-crash retrenchment. But many have found the pool of MBA talent has shrunk. `` This year we've had more people turn down jobs than in the past five years,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> partner who spoke at the Northwestern conference. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, manager of professional recruiting at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>, said although his firm hunted for fewer MBAs this year, `` student interest was down on campus, I have to be very direct with you about that.'' Although <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> had no trouble filling positions, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said `` with the downturn in the market, students were starting to think about less risk-oriented careers.'' The shift has been welcomed by major consulting and accounting firms, which are enjoying strong growth and seeking thousands of additional MBA graduates. At <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, for example, recruiters expect to hire 8,000 new employees this year, said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinbach </PERSON>, a managing partner. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a Touche <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> partner with recruiting responsibilities, said he has noticed much stronger interest from leading schools. `` At <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, we saw 230 people, more than we've ever seen before,'' <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said. `` Previously, we've seen 150, 160.'' <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said at least some of those additional applicants had been pursuing a Wall Street career prior to October. `` I think those always interested in investment banking are still interviewing,'' <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said. `` Others have been sobered by what's happened.''
