<HEAD>City Remains Cautious; Real Estate Soft; Job Outlook Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the epicenter of last October's stock market quake, remains jumpy at any aftershocks and watches warily for warning signs of future trouble `` So far, so good,'' is the opinion of <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrenhalt </PERSON>, the regional commissioner of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. `` The economy has held up better than most expected, but we still have n't got the situation fully in focus.'' Among the fuzzy images, six months later: _ The city, whose financial worries faded during the bull market, has scaled back its plans for growth The goal of a 30,000-member police department is on hold, two firehouses are closed, and museums and libraries found their budgets cut. _ The real estate market, though still inflated by standards of most <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities, has lost some steam, with office vacancy rates up, several construction projects on hold and condos no longer guaranteed to skyrocket in value _ Unemployment figures remain stable overall, but layoffs in the financial sector may show up in the statistics later as severance pay runs out for some and as businesses that depend on Wall Street are forced to follow suit The city adopted a cautious stance almost immediately after the crash. Within 10 days, Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> had ordered a 90-day hiring freeze. `` We needed the three months to evaluate what the crash meant,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Shorris </PERSON>, deputy director of the city Office of Management and Budget. The city recalculated its projections for fiscal 1989 _ July 1 to June 30, 1989 _ and figured its tax revenues would be about $ 270 million less than expected. `` A lot of people were doomsayers, taking terrible, grim positions'' after the crash, <PERSON> Shorris </PERSON> said. `` In context, $ 270 million out of a tax base of $ 14 billion is hardly a major change. But there was a reduction of growth.'' The slowdown in the local economy will force the city to keep a tight rein on spending. Plans to expand the <ORGANIZATION> Sanitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> were cut by 260 positions. The Department of Cultural Affairs saw its fiscal 1989 budget cut by $ 5.6 million; libraries will get $ 7.7 million less than originally expected, which will probably result in shorter hours and other cuts in services. Yet <PERSON> Shorris </PERSON> said the true effect of the crash shows up not so much in the data about the city that pours into his office, but in conversations and attitudes across the nation. `` More than the crash itself, it was reevaluation of nation's economy that was the most important byproduct,'' <PERSON> Shorris </PERSON> said `` That has a very important effect on us. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> has been more affected than almost any other city or state because of the high concentration of security and finance activity.'' One obvious casualty of the crash was a two-tower office complex planned for the southwest corner of Central Park, with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> as the prime tenant. Though the firm gave a variety of reasons for pulling out of the project, the crash and subsequent cutbacks contributed. That also hurt the city, which was counting on selling the property for $ 455 million, including $ 40 million in subway improvements. `` There's really been a reassessment of new construction. Several projects have been put on hold as a result of Black Monday,'' said <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynford </PERSON>, a real estate market analyst and publisher of an industry newsletter. The office vacancy rate was at 9 -LCB- percent in October and may be in the 14 percent range by the end of this year, <PERSON> Lynford </PERSON> said, noting that one percentage point represents 3.5 million square feet _ or more than half of one of the World Trade Center towers. In the residential market, he said, `` Unless you're talking about the premier residential units in the city, there has been and will be a comparatively more sluggish market than it has been the last couple of years, with slower rates of appreciation.'' Much of the shifting in the real estate market, both office and residential, can be traced to job cuts in the financial services industry, he said. From 1982 to 1987, 25 percent of the city's job growth was in financial services. `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is making a new transition into an economic environment characterized by uncertainty, risk and vulnerability in its dependence for growth on Wall Street and the financial industry,'' said <PERSON> Ehrenhalt </PERSON>. `` We're not out of the woods yet.''
</TEXT>
