<FIRST>u f PM-MousePatent 1stLd-Writethru f0150 04-12 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mouse Patent, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0150,0427</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with announcement; also moving general news
wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> was granted a patent for a genetically altered mouse today, the first time a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> patent has been issued for an animal. The laboratory mice were altered to make them more susceptible to cancer, and have been in use in experiments at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> since 1984, said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lilliam </PERSON> <PERSON> Blacker </PERSON>. Patent Commissioner <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigg </PERSON> said using the animal will simplify cancer research and make it easier to test both cancer-causing substances and chemicals that fight cancer. The action drew fire from <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON>, who heads a coalition of groups opposed to genetic engineering. He termed the action a usurpation of power by the <ORGANIZATION> Patent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, noting that there have been discussions in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of imposing a moratorium on such patents until ethical questions can be worked out. <PERSON> Quigg </PERSON>, however, said that the patent application, which was filed in 1984, met the legal criteria for a patent, and so one was issued. Ethical questions, he said, need to be settled in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the medical laboratories, not the Patent Office. While this was the first patent on an animal, plants and forms of bacteria have been patented previously. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 ruled that man-made life organisms could be patented, but the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> patent is the first to protect a genetic change in a higher life form. The patent was issued to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, with the inventors listed as <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Leder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>. <PERSON> Quigg </PERSON> said his office has 21 other applications for animal patents pending. Details could not be disclosed, however, he said. He said that virtually any changed animal could be patented, except humans. Patents allow the inventor the exclusive right to use a product for 17 years, although in practice the patent holder usually licenses use of the product for a fee. `` This opens the floodgates for a whole range of patents, from fish to house pets,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which supports a moratorium on animal patents. But <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Karny </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> patent attorney, said the action was `` not a radical departure from existing policy.'' `` Granting a patent on animals is an entirely logical application of existing patent law principles, and in many respects is nothing different from what society has been doing with regard to the commercial ownership of animals for thousands of years.''
</TEXT>
