<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fiscal 1989 budget hides the true size of the federal deficit because it factors in huge surpluses from the Social Security system and other programs, senators said Tuesday while considering the $ 1.1 trillion spending plan. By an 85-8 vote, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> gave preliminary approval to an amendment to the budget urging the lawmakers to discount the surpluses amassed by two funds set aside for highway and aviation projects when calculating the federal deficit. The two funds have a combined projected surplus of $ 2 billion for next year. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget blueprint officially predicts the deficit problem is easing. But under an amendment offered by Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the budget committee, the mammoth surplus the Social Security program accumulates each year would no longer be counted when figuring the federal deficit That amendment could be voted on as early as Wednesday. `` The deficit is heading up, not down,'' said <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget, which <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> helped write, predicts the red ink will shrink to $ 136 billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, a drop of more than $ 10 billion from the amount anticipated in the current fiscal year. However, that counts a $ 46 billion surplus in Social Security, which is expected to grow even larger through the beginning of the next century. The funds then would be expended when the Baby Boom generation reaches retirement age. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., said that even if the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and president meet their promise under the Gramm-Rudman law for a balanced budget by fiscal 1993, the deficit that year actually would be more than $ 100 billion if the Social Security surplus is n't counted Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, R-Wash., said he thought the amendment was an inadequate gesture and that major revisions of the federal accounting system were needed, not just non-binding legislative language There was less debate about the substance of the budget, which would carry out the mandate of last fall's deficit-reduction agreement between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and congressional leaders. The spending plan, like the agreement, calls for $ 294 billion in military spending, $ 16.1 billion for foreign assistance and $ 169.2 billion for domestic agencies, outside of entitlements and other programs set by automatic formulas. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan features a 27 percent increase in spending on the space program and big boosts in AIDS research, both requested by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Education would receive $ 1.2 billion, a 7.4 percent boost. Like the president's plan, the budget does n't call for new taxes beyond the $ 14 billion for fiscal 1988 which was enacted last December. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan also calls for: _ A 4.3 percent pay increase for the military and 2 percent for civilian federal workers <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had requested the different pay boosts, but the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted for 3 percent across the board. _ $ 500 million for more farm commodities for the poor, to replace exhausted surplus stocks. _ Expansion of Medicaid health program and enactment of Medicare catastrophic illness insurance, assuming fees raised to pay for them _ An 11 percent increase for <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for its research programs and a 25 percent increase in <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> nuclear physics program, toward development of the superconducting super collider project _ A 3 percent cut in rural housing assistance, along with reductions in elderly housing and community and regional development _ Aviation safety increase of 19 percent from $ 5.5 billion this year, to hire 900 more air traffic controllers and modernize the system The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget, approved last month, also follows the overall budget guidelines of last fall but it differs in detail from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted to spend more on aid to local communities and less on space than the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan. The two chambers must agree on a single spending plan, after which it serves as a guide for regular fiscal legislation. The budget is a congressional resolution that does not require the president's signature. The official deadline for completing the budget is Friday. Although <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is unlikely to meet that target, this year's budget action is coming at the earliest dates in years
