<HEAD>Pepperell Overall Earnings Down, Continuing Operations Income Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point-Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday its net income declined 2.1 percent in its second quarter, although income from continuing operations rose 22.4 percent. The West Point-based company, which is involved in a billion-dollar bidding war for rival textile giant <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stevens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, reported net income of $ 15.3 million, or 51 cents per share, in the quarter ended March 26. That compared with a profit of $ 15.6 million, or 53 cents per share, in the same quarter last year. Sales for the quarter totaled $ 459.9 million, up 12 percent from $ 410.4 million in the year-earlier quarter. Income from continuing operations rose to $ 18.6 million from $ 15.2 million a year earlier. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, stated the rise in operating earnings stemmed from solid sales increases in knit apparel fabrics and in the company's bed and bath lines and from lower tax rates in 1988. <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> said the company had an after-tax charge of $ 3.3 million against a gain on the sale of discontinued carpet operations. West Point sold substantially all of its assets of its carpet and rug division last November to <ORGANIZATION> Shaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. For the first six months of its fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 40.9 million, up 11.8 percent from the previous period's $ 36.6 million Per-share earnings rose to $ 1.34 from $ 1.25 in the previous quarter. Sales for the first half were $ 940.9 million, up 12.9 percent from $ 833.1 million a year earlier. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> is dueling with <ORGANIZATION> Odyssey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> for control of <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stevens </ORGANIZATION>. New York-based <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> has entered a merger agreement with Odyssey, an investment group, but <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> has continued bidding for the company. Odyssey on Monday offered $ 1.22 billion for <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, topping <ORGANIZATION> Pepperell </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 1.19 billion bid made earlier in the day. <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> has said <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> may consider topping Odyssey's latest price.
