<HEAD>Greenspan: Banking Reserves Must Be Increased To Handle Global
Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hazards of deregulated banking on a global scale demand that banks increase their reserves, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the need for bigger bank reserves was underscored last year when major banks took big losses because of reserves set aside to cover bad loans to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. For some banks, those moves erased most of a decade's worth of growth in their capital reserves. Such losses might be digested by healthy banks in a stable domestic economy, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said. But the volatile nature of international lending and increasing bank involvement in real estate, insurance and securities brokering demanded a bigger safety net, he told the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION>. Last December, federal banking officials and supervisory officials from the 10 largest industrialized nations jointly proposed establishing uniform international capital requirements. The plan would set an internationally accepted minimum equity capital requirement and a menu of acceptable non-traditional assets that could supplement a bank's equity base. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the plan should be viewed as a crude first step in focusing attention on the need for additional reserves. `` Some revisions may be required over time, but it provides an important base to allow bank organizations to adapt in years ahead,'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said.
